{"title_page": "Legal recognition of sign languages", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe '''legal recognition of sign languages''' differs widely. In some jurisdictions (countries, states, provinces or regions), a [[sign language]] is an official language, whereas in others it has a protected status in certain areas such as education. Governments sometimes stipulate in their constitutions or laws that 'sign language' is recognised or protected, but they fail to specify ''which'' sign language exactly, as there may be several different sign languages in common use within its borders, which has led to problems.\n\nExtending legal recognition is one of the major concerns of the international [[Deaf community]], however, symbolic recognition is no guarantee for an effective improvement of the life of sign language users, and it has been argued that sign languages should be recognized and supported not merely as an accommodation for the disabled, but as the communication medium of language communities.<ref>Sarah C. E. Batterbury. 2012. ''Language Policy'' 11:253\u2013272.</ref>\n\n==Sign language status by state==\n\n===Australia===\n[[Auslan]] was recognised by the Australian Government as a \"community language other than English\" and the preferred language of the Deaf community in policy statements in 1987 and 1991. This recognition does not ensure any provision of services in Auslan, but use of Auslan in Deaf education and provision of Auslan/English interpreters is becoming more common.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|It is now increasingly recognised that signing deaf people constitute a group like any other non-English speaking language group in Australia, with a distinct sub-culture recognised by shared history, social life and sense of identity, united and symbolised by fluency in Auslan, the principal means of communication within the Australian Deaf Community.|||Australia's Language: The Australian Language and Literacy Policy (page 20). (Australian Government Publishing Service, Canberra, 1991)}}\n\n===Austria===\n[[Austrian Sign Language]] (\u00d6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprache, \u00d6GS) was recognised by the Austrian Parliament in 2005. On 1 September 2005 the Austrian Constitution was amended to include a new article: \"\u00a78 (3) Die \u00d6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprache ist als eigenst\u00e4ndige Sprache anerkannt. Das N\u00e4here bestimmen die Gesetze.\u201c (\"Austrian Sign Language is recognised as independent language. The laws will determine the details.\")<ref>Krausneker, Verena (2005) \u00d6sterreichs erste Minderheitensprache, in: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070310204101/http://minderheiten.at/stimme/stimme56f.htmSTIMME von und f\u00fcr Minderheiten # 56]</ref><ref>Krausneker, Verena (2006) ''Taubstumm bis geb\u00e4rdensprachig. Die \u00f6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprachgemeinschaft aus soziolinguistischer Perspektive.'' Verlag Drava.</ref>\n\n===Belgium===\n\n====French Community====\nThe [[Parliament of the French Community|Parliament]] of the [[French Community of Belgium]] recognised [[French Belgian Sign Language]] (LSFB) in a [[decree]] of October 2003. This recognition entails:\n# a cultural (symbolical) recognition and\n# the foundation of a commission that will advise the Government of the French Community in all matters related to LSFB.\n\nIn [https://web.archive.org/web/20041105050456/http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_officiel.pdf ''D\u00e9cret relatif \u00e0 la reconnaissance de la langue des signes''] (Decree on the recognition of the sign language), from three possible legal interpretations of the term 'recognition',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_LS.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2006-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927092446/http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_LS.pdf#page=8 |archive-date=2006-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the following one was retained: \"It concerns a symbolic recognition that goes hand in hand with a general measure, permitting every minister to take action in fields relative to his authority.\"<ref name=\"walloon\">\"... il s'agit d'une reconnaissance cadre assortie d'une mesure d'ex\u00e9cution g\u00e9n\u00e9rale permettant \u00e0 chaque ministre concern\u00e9 de prendre les arr\u00eat\u00e9s d'application relevant de ses comp\u00e9tences ...\"</ref>\n\n====Flemish Community====\n[[Flemish Sign Language]] was recognised on 2006-04-26 by the [[Flemish Parliament]]. This recognition entails:\n# a cultural (symbolical) recognition (see excerpt below),\n# the foundation of a commission that will advise the Flemish government in all matters related to VGT and\n# the structural funding of research and development of VGT.\nThis recognition was accelerated by the most successful petition ever with the Flemish Parliament and the presence of a Deaf member of parliament, Helga Stevens, and her interpreters in the Flemish Parliament.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|Cultural recognition entails that the Flemish Government recognises the Flemish Sign Language as the language of the Deaf Community in Flanders. This 'recognition' encompasses the following three meanings: (1) the Flemish Government acknowledges the correctness of the fact that the Flemish Sign Language is the language of the Deaf Community in Flanders, (2) the Flemish Government also accepts the existence of this language in the judicial domain and treats it accordingly and (3) the Flemish Government expresses its respect for this language.<ref name=\"flemish\">\"Die 'erkenning' omvat hierbij de drie betekennissen van het woord: (1) de Vlaamse overheid bevestigt de juistheid van het feit dat de Vlaamse Gebarentaal de taal is van de Dovengemeenschap in Vlaanderen, (2) de Vlaamse overheid aanvaardt het bestaan van die taal ook op juridisch vlak en behandelt ze als dustanig en (3) de Vlaamse overheid uit haar waardering voor deze taal.\"</ref>|||[http://jsp.vlaamsparlement.be/docs/stukken/2005-2006/g729-1.pdf Decreet houdende de erkenning van de Vlaamse Gebarentaal] (Decree on the recognition of the Flemish Sign Language)}}\n\n===Brazil===\nThe [[Brazilian Sign Language|Brazilian Sign Language (LIBRAS)]] was legally recognized in 2002 but can't replace written [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]];<ref name=\"Brazil 2002\">[http://planalto.gov.br/CCIVIL_03/LEIS/2002/L10436.htm , April 24, 2002].</ref> the law was [[regulation|regulated]] in 2005.<ref name=\"Brazil 2005\">[http://www.planalto.gov.br/ccivil_03/_ato2004-2006/2005/decreto/d5626.htm Brazilian decree n\u00ba 5626, December 22, 2005].</ref> The language must be taught as a part of the [[school of education|education]] and [[speech and language pathology]] curricula, and law also mandates that LIBRAS be an elective subject as part of every other undergraduate course. LIBRAS teachers, instructors and translators are recognized professionals. Schools and health services must provide access (\"[[inclusion (education)|include]]\") to deaf people.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Canada===\nThe [[Accessible Canada Act]], passed on 21 June 2019, recognised '[[American Sign Language]], [[Quebec Sign Language]] and Indigenous sign languages (...) as the primary languages for communication by deaf persons in Canada.'<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://laws.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/A-0.6/page-1.html |title=Accessible Canada Act S.C. 2019, c. 10 |publisher=Canadian Ministry of Justice |date=21 June 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestion Period in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] is interpreted in both [[Quebec Sign Language]] and [[American Sign Language]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} [[Section Fourteen of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms]] specifies that an accused person who does not understand the language in which his or her trial is carried out, or is deaf, is entitled to an interpreter.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn several of Canada's provinces ([[Manitoba]] in 1988, [[Alberta]] in 1990, [[Ontario]] in 1993), [[ASL]] is an officially recognised minority language with legally embedded rights.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOntario recognised ASL and LSQ as a language in which the Deaf can be taught when it altered its Education Act in 1993. Ontario formally recognised ASL in 2007 attributing to it the rights of fellow minority languages.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Inuit Sign Language|Inuit or Inuktitut Sign Language]] (IUR) is used in Canada's arctic communities, and was developed locally by families and communities who found a need for their deaf families and community members. Deaf Inuit who have attended school in Canada's south have also learned ASL. IUR made its debut in Nunavut legislature in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/inuit-sign-language-makes-debut-in-nunavut-legislature-1.772092|title=Inuit sign language makes debut in Nunavut legislature - CBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maritime Sign Language]] (MSL), which derives from the [[British Sign Language]], is a moribund sign language in Canada's [[The Maritimes|Maritime Provinces]].<ref name=CBC>{{cite news |first=Emma |last=Davie |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/preserving-maritime-sign-language-msl-deaf-community-1.5402328 |title=How the deaf community is preserving Maritime Sign Language |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=31 December 2019}}</ref> It does not have any official recognition and is no longer instructed in schools, having been replaced by American Sign Language.<ref name=CBC/> The MSL-teaching [[Halifax School for the Deaf]] operated from 1856 to June 1961, after which the Interprovincial School for the Education of the Deaf (later renamed Atlantic Provinces Special Education Authority, APSEA) in [[Amherst, Nova Scotia]] took over until it closed in 1995.<ref name=CBC/><ref>{{Cite book |last=Marsh |first=James H. |date=1999 |title=The Canadian Encyclopedia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wR_-aSFyvuYC&pg=PA640 |location=Toronto, Ontario |publisher=McClelland & Stewart Inc. |page=640 |isbn=9780771020995 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chile===\nChilean Sign Language (LSCh), Chile enacted in Law No. 20,422, in 2010 in order to ensure the right to equality of opportunity for disabled people, negating any form of discrimination against them. And which recognizes sign language as the natural means of communication of the deaf community.<ref>[http://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idLey=20422 Ley 20422 BCN LEGISLACI\u00d3N CHILENA, 2010]</ref>\n\n===Czech Republic===\n[[Czech Sign Language]] gained legal recognition as a human language with the passage of the Sign Language Law 155/1998 Sb (\"Z\u00e1kon o znakov\u00e9 \u0159e\u010di 155/1998 Sb\").<ref>{{in lang|cs}} {{cite web|url=http://www.sagit.cz/pages/sbirkatxt.asp?zdroj=sb98155&cd=76&typ=r |title=Z\u00c1KON ze dne 11. \u010dervna 1998 o znakov\u00e9 \u0159e\u010di a o zm\u011bn\u011b dal\u0161\u00edch z\u00e1kon\u016f - Sb\u00edrka z\u00e1kon\u016f - Nakladatelstv\u00ed Sagit, a.s |publisher=Sagit.cz |date=2000-12-01 |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\n===Denmark===\n\nAs of 13 May 2014, [[Danish Sign Language]] gained legal recognition. The Danish Parliament established The Danish Sign Language Council \"to devise principles and guidelines for the monitoring of the Danish sign language and offer advice and information on the Danish sign language.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsn.dk/tegnsprog/about-the-danish-sign-language-council|title=The Danish Sign Language Council \u2014 Dansk Sprogn\u00e6vn|website=www.dsn.dk}}</ref>\n\n===European Union===\nThe [[European Parliament]] unanimously approved a resolution about Deaf Sign Languages on 17 June 1988 (available online here<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.policy.hu/flora/ressign2.htm |title=Published by: EUD |publisher=Policy.hu |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>). The resolution indirectly asks all member states for recognition of their sign languages as official languages of the Deaf.\n\n{{cquote|The European Parliament [...] calls on the Commission to make a proposal to the Council concerning official recognition of the sign language used by deaf people in each Member State.|||[http://www.policy.hu/flora/ressign2.htm European Parliament Resolution on Sign Languages 1988]}}\n\nThe EP issued another resolution in 1998 with more or less the same content as in 1988, (see RESOLUTION on sign languages for the deaf, Official Journal C 187, 18/07/1988 P. 0236 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CELEX:51987IP0302:EN:NOT |title=EUR-Lex - 51987IP0302 - EN - EUR-Lex |publisher=Eur-lex.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\nA third resolution was passed in 2016, drafted by Helga Stevens MEP, Europe's first deaf female MEP, a lawyer, and former Executive Director and subsequent President of the European Union of the Deaf. This resolution is on \"Sign language and professional sign language interpreters\". The text in this resolution is more sophisticated than preceding European Parliamentary resolutions, demonstrating the expertise of the author and also the increased maturity of the communities working towards increased recognition of sign language (e.g. drawing on academic expertise in Deaf Studies, interpreting studies, linguistics, etc.)<ref>http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/TA-8-2016-0442_EN.html</ref>\n\n===Finland===\n[[Finnish Sign Language]] was recognised in the constitution in August 1995.\n\n{{cquote|''Section 17 - Right to one's language and culture'' [...] The rights of persons using sign language and of persons in need of interpretation or translation aid owing to disability shall be guaranteed by an Act.<ref name=\"finnish\">17 \u00a7 Oikeus omaan kieleen ja kulttuuriin [...] Viittomakielt\u00e4 k\u00e4ytt\u00e4vien sek\u00e4 vammaisuuden vuoksi tulkitsemisja k\u00e4\u00e4nn\u00f6sapua tarvitsevien oikeudet turvataan lailla. (Ministry of Justice, Finland: [http://www.finlex.fi/linkit/ajansd/19990731000 ''Suomen perustuslaki''].)</ref>|||[http://www.om.fi/uploads/54begu60narbnv_1.pdf The Constitution of Finland]}}\n\n===Iceland===\n[[Icelandic Sign Language]] was recognised by law in education in 2004.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|This National Curriculum Guide contains, for the first time, provisions on special Icelandic instruction for students whose mother tongue is not Icelandic. There are also new provisions on special Icelandic instruction for deaf and hearing-impaired pupils and sign-language instruction for the deaf. The objectives for Icelandic instruction of immigrants and the deaf and of sign-language instruction fall under the subject area of language arts (Icelandic) in compulsory school. [...]\n\nSign language is of basic importance for the development of language, personality and thinking of deaf children. For the deaf, sign language is the most important source of knowledge and their route to participation in Icelandic culture and the culture of the deaf. Sign language is of great importance for all school work and for the pupils' life and work.<ref name=\"icelandic\">\u00cd a\u00f0aln\u00e1mskr\u00e1 grunnsk\u00f3la eru \u00ed fyrsta sinn sett \u00e1kv\u00e6\u00f0i um s\u00e9rstaka \u00edslenskukennslu fyrir nemendur me\u00f0 anna\u00f0 m\u00f3\u00f0urm\u00e1l en \u00edslensku. Einnig eru n\u00fd \u00e1kv\u00e6\u00f0i um s\u00e9rstaka \u00edslenskukennslu fyrir heyrnarlausa og heyrnarskerta nemendur og t\u00e1knm\u00e1lskennslu fyrir heyrnarlausa. Markmi\u00f0 fyrir \u00edslenskukennslu n\u00fdb\u00faa og heyrnarlausra og t\u00e1knm\u00e1lskennslu falla undir n\u00e1mssvi\u00f0 \u00edslensku \u00ed grunnsk\u00f3la. [...]\n\nT\u00e1knm\u00e1l hefur grundvallar\u00fe\u00fd\u00f0ingu fyrir \u00feroska m\u00e1ls, pers\u00f3nuleika og hugsunar heyrnarlausra nemenda. Hj\u00e1 heyrnarlausum er t\u00e1knm\u00e1li\u00f0 mikilv\u00e6gasta uppspretta \u00feekkingar og lei\u00f0 til a\u00f0 taka \u00fe\u00e1tt \u00ed \u00edslenskri menningu og menningu heyrnarlausra. T\u00e1knm\u00e1li\u00f0 hefur mikla \u00fe\u00fd\u00f0ingu fyrir alla vinnu \u00ed sk\u00f3lanum og fyrir l\u00edf og starf nemendanna. (Ministry of Education, Science and Culture: [http://bella.stjr.is/utgafur/AGalmennurhluti.pdf ''A\u00f0aln\u00e1mskr\u00e1 grunnsk\u00f3la: Almennur hluti''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927194051/http://bella.stjr.is/utgafur/AGalmennurhluti.pdf |date=2007-09-27 }})</ref>|||4=[http://bella.mrn.stjr.is/utgafur/general.pdf#page=23 The National Curriculum Guide for Compulsory School (Ministry of Education, Science and Culture, 2004)] (official translation)}}\n\nOn 27 May 2011, the Icelandic Parliament unanimously approved a bill which recognises Icelandic Sign Language as an official minority language with constitutional rights and as the first language of the deaf people of [[Iceland]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Indian subcontinent===\nThere is no official recognition of [[Indo-Pakistani Sign Language]] (IPSL), which is well-documented, widely used throughout the [[Indian subcontinent]] across national and state borders with few regional variations, and has over a million estimated users in [[India]] alone, is also commonly used in [[Pakistan]] and probably also in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Evans |first=Nicholas |title=Reciprocals and Semantic Typology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U020QQv1Qn4C&pg=PA95 |location=Amsterdam & Philadelphia |publisher=John Benjamins Publishing |page=95 |isbn=9789027206794 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Ireland===\nIrish Sign Language was given official recognition in 2017. The \"Recognition of Irish Sign Language for the Deaf Community Bill 2016\" passed all stages in the [[Oireachtas]] (Irish Parliament) on 14 December 2017, and was signed into law by the [[President of Ireland]] [[Michael D. Higgins|Michael D Higgins]] on 24 December 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/irish-sign-language-given-official-legal-recognition-1.3338081|title=Irish Sign Language given official legal recognition|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2017/1224/929482-sign-language-bill/|title=President signs Irish Sign Language bill into law|date=2017-12-24|work=RTE.ie|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en}}</ref> Prior to 2017, there was no automatic right for deaf people to have an ISL [[Language interpretation|interpreter]] (except for criminal court proceedings). For the deaf community, recognition of ISL means more legal rights and better access to [[public service]]s - including [[Education in the Republic of Ireland|education]], [[Healthcare in the Republic of Ireland|healthcare]], [[Media of the Republic of Ireland|media]] and [[banking]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2017/1213/927259-irish-sign-language/|title=D\u00e1il passes 'historic' sign language legislation|date=2017-12-14|work=RTE.ie|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/irish-sign-language-set-to-be-given-official-status-36407921.html|title=Irish Sign Language set to be given official status - Independent.ie|work=Independent.ie|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/irish-sign-language-set-to-receive-official-recognition-818648.html|title=Irish sign language set to receive official recognition|date=2017-12-14|work=Breaking News|access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref>\n\n===Italy===\nThere is no official recognition of [[Italian Sign Language]] (''Lingua dei Segni Italiana'', LIS) yet. Those who oppose LIS recognition say this language is \"grammarless,\" although, by definition, a [[Language#The properties of language|language]] cannot be, in fact, grammarless. Several research on the matter have already shown that [[Italian Sign Language]] is a proper language.<ref>[http://michelebrunelli.interfree.it/GrammLIS_e_Restrittive.pdf Michele Brunelli: Grammatica della LIS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722035622/http://michelebrunelli.interfree.it/GrammLIS_e_Restrittive.pdf |date=2011-07-22 }}</ref>\n\n===Kenya===\nThe 2010 [[Constitution of Kenya]] recognises [[Kenyan Sign Language]] and states that the state shall promote the development and use of Kenyan Sign Language (Article 7.3b). Sign language is recognised further in Article 120 (1) which states that 'the official languages of Parliament are [[Swahili language|Kiswahili]], [[English language|English]] and Kenyan Sign Language and the business of Parliament may be conducted in English, Kiswahili and Kenyan Sign Language.'<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://kenyalaw.org:8181/exist/kenyalex/actview.xql?actid=Const2010 |title=Constitution of Kenya, 2010 |work=Kenya Law |publisher=Judiciary of Kenya |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Malta ===\nThe [[Maltese Sign Language]] (LSM) was official recognized by parliament in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/63266/parliament_gives_maltese_sign_language_official_recognition|title=Parliament gives Maltese sign language official recognition}}</ref>\n\n=== Mexico ===\n\nThe [[Mexican Sign Language]] (LSM) was officially declared a \"national language\" in 2003, and it started being used in public deaf education thereafter.<ref>Ley Federal para las Personas con Discapacidad.  http://www.diputados.gob.mx/LeyesBiblio/pdf/262.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150616003344/http://www.diputados.gob.mx/LeyesBiblio/pdf/262.pdf |date=2015-06-16 }}</ref> Before 2003, deaf education in the country was focused on oralism (speech and lipreading) with few schools conducting classes in LSM.<ref>Karla Faurot, Dianne Dellinger, Andy Eatough, Steve Parkhurst (1992, revised 1998 and 2001) The identity of Mexican sign as a language. http://www.sil.org/silesr/2000/2000-002/ \u00a9 1999 Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\nAlthough [[Nepali Sign Language]] has not yet been officially recognized as the [[mother tongue]] of Nepal's deaf population, legislation is underway which will bring Nepali law in line with the provisions of the UN [[Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities]]. These laws will recognize the rights of the deaf to use [[Nepali Sign Language]] have it used in education, in social life, in the legal sphere, etc., and this should thus lead to official governmental recognition of [[Nepali Sign Language]] on a par with the various spoken languages of Nepal.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Netherlands===\n[[File:Nederlandse gebarentaal krijgt eindelijk een zichtbare plek in onze samenleving.webm|thumb|[[Roelof van Laar]] explaining the 2016 bill to recognise NGT]]\nThe [[Dutch Sign Language]] (NGT) has not been recognised officially by law. In 2010, the [[Christian Union (Netherlands)|Christian Union]] party introduced a bill to recognise NGT, but it did not pass.<ref name=\"AD2016\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.ad.nl/nieuws/erken-nederlandse-gebarentaal-als-officiele-taal~a5a253f6/ |title=Erken Nederlandse gebarentaal als offici\u00eble taal |publisher=Algemeen Dagblad |date=3 October 2016 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref>\nIn October 2016, this was followed by a bill from MPs [[Roelof van Laar]] ([[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour Party]]) and [[Carla Dik-Faber]] (Christian Union) for legal recognition of NGT as an official language.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2016/10/03/gebarentaal-moet-erkend-worden-als-officiele-taal-a1524573|title=PvdA en CU: erken gebarentaal als offici\u00eble taal|author=Beila Heilbron|publisher=NRC Handelsblad|date=3 October 2016 |language=nl}}</ref> After Van Laar's departure, MP [[Attje Kuiken]] (Labour Party) took over the bill in September 2019, while MP [[Jessica van Eijs]] ([[Democrats 66]]) joined Kuiken and Dik-Faber.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.eerstekamer.nl/behandeling/20190927/brief_lid_fractie_brief_van_de/document3/f=/vl29hrq7v1yn.pdf |title=Voorstel van wet van de leden Van Laar en Dik-Faber ter erkenning van Nederlandse gebarentaal (Wet erkenning Nederlandse gebarentaal) |author=Attje Kuiken & Carla Dik-Faber |work=Brief van de leden Kuiken en Dik-Faber |publisher=Senate of the Netherlands |date=27 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nos.nl/nieuwsuur/artikel/2300498-initiatiefwet-nederlandse-gebarentaal-erkennen-als-officiele-taal.html |title=Initiatiefwet: Nederlandse Gebarentaal erkennen als offici\u00eble taal |author=Linda de Groot |work=Nieuwsuur |publisher=NOS |date=5 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref> At the end of September 2019 the Advisory Division of the [[Council of State (Netherlands)|Council of State]] stated that the text of the bill was still too vague, as it did not make clear which problems it exactly intended to address and through which practical means; for example, it asked whether 'the Deaf culture' \u2013 mentioned in the bill \u2013 also needed to be legally recognised, and if so, what that term precisely entailed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.raadvanstate.nl/@117458/samenvatting-gebarentaal/ |title=Samenvatting advies initiatiefwetsvoorstel erkenning Nederlandse gebarentaal |publisher=Advisory Division of the Council of State |date=30 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\n[[New Zealand Sign Language]] became the third official language of [[New Zealand]] in April 2006, joining [[M\u0101ori language|English and M\u0101ori]] when the bill was passed in the New Zealand Parliament on 6 April 2006.<ref>McKee, R. 2007. The eyes have it! Our third official language\u2013New Zealand Sign Language. ''Journal of New Zealand Studies'', NS 4-5.129-148.</ref>\n\n{{cquote|Part 2 cl 6: New Zealand Sign Language is declared to be an official language of New Zealand.|||[http://www.odi.govt.nz/documents/nzds/nzsl-bill.pdf New Zealand Sign Language Bill]}}\n\n=== North Macedonia ===\nThe [[Macedonian Sign Language]] (''\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043d \u0458\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, Makedonski znakoven jazik'') is officially recognized as a \"natural way of communication between the people\". The language is regulated by a law, which allows students and every individual in [[North Macedonia]] to study the language. Also, the law secures the right of the interpreter for the students with special needs, and every other deaf person can request an interpreter, as well.<ref name=\"\u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\">''[http://www.deafmkd.org.mk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=57&Itemid=82&lang=mk \u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0437\u0430 \u0443\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \u043d\u0430  \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043e\u0442 \u0458\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0435\u043d \u0432\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430, \u0431\u0440\u043e\u0458 105, 21 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442 2009, \u0421\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0458\u0435]''</ref> Currently,{{when|date=April 2020}} there are more than 6.000 Macedonian citizens with deafness.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Northern Ireland===\nIn Northern Ireland, both [[British Sign Language]] and [[Irish Sign Language]] (but not [[Northern Ireland Sign Language]]) were recognised as official languages by the [[Northern Ireland Office]] in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nio.gov.uk/paul-murphy-announces-recognition-for-sign-language/media-detail.htm?newsID=8540 |title=Paul Murphy announces recognition for sign language |accessdate=2008-06-22 |date=2004-03-30 |publisher=[[Northern Ireland Office]] |quote=I am pleased to announce formal recognition for both British and Irish Sign Languages in Northern Ireland. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520115301/http://www.nio.gov.uk/paul-murphy-announces-recognition-for-sign-language/media-detail.htm?newsID=8540 |archivedate=2011-05-20 }}</ref> but they don't yet have the same status as the province's two official minority languages, [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[Ulster Scots language|Ulster-Scots]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Norway===\n[[Norwegian Sign Language]] is recognised by law in education.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Papua New Guinea===\nIn May 2015, [[Papua New Guinean Sign Language]] became the fourth official language of [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref name=\"sil.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sil.org/about/news/two-sign-languages-given-official-language-status|title=Two Sign Languages Given Official Language Status|date=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Philippines ===\nArticle 3 of Republic Act No. 11106 declared [[Filipino Sign Language]] as the national sign language of the [[Philippines]], specifying that it shall be recognized, supported and promoted as the medium of official communication in all transactions involving the deaf, and as the language of instruction of deaf education.<ref>{{cite act |url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/downloads/2018/10oct/20181030-RA-11106-RRD.pdf|title=The Filipino Sign Language Act|type=Republic act|number=11106|article=3|work=Official Gazette |publisher=Government of the Philippines|date=30 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Genalyn Kabiling |work=Manila Bulletin |title=Filipino Sign Language declared as nat\u2019l sign language of Filipino deaf |date=12 November 2018 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2018/11/12/filipino-sign-language-declared-as-natl-sign-language-of-filipino-deaf/ |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Portugal===\n{{cquote|Art. 74, 2 (h): In implementing the education policy, the state shall be charged with protecting and developing Portuguese sign language, as an expression of culture and an instrument for access to education and equal opportunities.<ref name=\"portuguese\">Na realiza\u00e7\u00e3o da pol\u00edtica de ensino incumbe ao Estado proteger e valorizar a l\u00edngua gestual portuguesa, enquanto express\u00e3o cultural e instrumento de acesso \u00e0 educa\u00e7\u00e3o e da igualdade de oportunidades. (Assembleia da Rep\u00fablica: [http://www.parlamento.pt/const_leg/crp_port/index.html Constitui\u00e7\u00e3o da rep\u00fablica portuguesa] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809203630/http://www.parlamento.pt/const_leg/crp_port/index.html |date=2007-08-09 }}</ref>|||[http://www.parlamento.pt/ingles/cons_leg/crp_ing/ Constitution of Portugal]}}\nAs an example, many shows (such as the news) in public channels ([[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]]) have one corner of the screen with a person translating what's being said into sign language.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n===Russia===\nRussian Sign Language (''\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0436\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a'') has very limited legal recognition. Under the Federal \"Law on Protection of People with Disabilities,\" the sign language is considered a language used for inter-personal communication only, which means that no state support for the language is provided.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\n=== Slovak Republic ===\n[[Slovak Sign Language]] was recognised in 1995 by law: \"Z\u00e1kon o posunkovej re\u010di nepo\u010duj\u00facich os\u00f4b 149/1995 Sb\" - the Law of the Sign Language of the Deaf 149/1995.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== South Africa ===\n[[South African Sign Language]] is not specifically recognised as a [[Languages of South Africa|Language of South Africa]] by the country's [[Constitution of South Africa|constitution]], instead it contains the phrase \"sign language\" in the generic sense.<ref>http://www.info.gov.za/documents/constitution/1996/96cons1.htm#6 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629092124/http://www.info.gov.za/documents/constitution/1996/96cons1.htm |date=2011-06-29 }}</ref>\nThere is a process underway in parliament to investigate the possibility of upgrading the status of SASL to become the country's 12th official language.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pmg.org.za/report/20091113-language-issues-proposed-recognition-south-african-sign-language-offi |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-10-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100515104619/http://www.pmg.org.za/report/20091113-language-issues-proposed-recognition-south-african-sign-language-offi |archive-date=2010-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\nOn 31 December 2015, the \"South Korean National Assembly passed legislation to recognize Korean Sign Language as one of Korea\u2019s official languages.\"<ref name=\"sil.org\"/>\n\n=== Spain ===\nOn 28 June 2007, Spanish and Catalan Sign Languages were recognised by the Spanish Parliament to be official languages in Spain. This recent legal development has opened a door to reinforced communication in the areas of healthcare, justice, education and MCM.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nSo far, the [[Autonomous communities of Spain|Autonomous Communities]] of [[Catalonia]], [[Andalusia]], and [[Valencia (autonomous community)|Valencia]] had granted the use of sign languages to the Deaf. In the other Spanish regions no sign languages were so far recognised, and support in terms of sign language interpretation for Deaf persons has been minimal or confined by different budgets. As pointed out, there are three sign languages claimed by Deaf organisations: [[Spanish Sign Language]], [[Catalan Sign Language]] (LSC) and [[Valencian Sign Language]] (LSPV), although some linguists consider these to be the same.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Catalonia====\nAlthough a regional law guarantees the presence of [[Catalan Sign Language]] since 1994 in all areas under the Catalan Government, such as education and media, until recently it was officially recognised the LSC in the [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia]] of 2006.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Andalusia====\nThe legal situation in Andalusia is similar to the one in Catalonia, where a regional Law guarantees the presence of the [[Spanish Sign Language]] (LSE) in all social scopes since 1998. Recently, a recognition of it is included in the reforming of their Statute of Autonomy. At the moment, Andalusia is the unique Community where LSE is recognised with regards to the rest of Spain. In any case, in linguistic terms, the LSE used there has a strong dialectal variation.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Valencia====\nUntil recently, Valencia had poor legal support for the Deaf. The approved 2006 Statute of Autonomy grants to Valencian Deaf their right to use [[Valencian Sign Language]] (LSPV or LSCV). (Though the statute refers only to \"sign language\" in a generic sense.){{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|Article 13,4: The Generalitat shall grant the use of the own sign language of deaf persons, which shall have to be purposed in education, protection and respect.<ref name=\"valencian\">La Generalitat garantir\u00e0 l\u2019\u00fas de la llengua de signes pr\u00f2pia de les persones sordes, que haur\u00e0 de ser objecte d\u2019ensenyament, protecci\u00f3 i respecte. (Corts Valencianes: [http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf Estatut d'Autonomia de la Communitat Valenciana] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926130504/http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf |date=2007-09-26 }}.)</ref>|||[http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf Statute of Autonomy of the Valencian Country]}}\n\n====Galicia====\n[[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] is said{{by whom|date=June 2012}} to be working on a bill concerning the recognition of a sign language.{{citation needed|date=June 2012}}\n\n=== Sri Lanka ===\nThe recognition of [[Sri Lankan sign languages|Sri Lankan Sign Language]] was accepted by [[Sri Lanka]] on 26 September 2010. According to the report by [[Sri Lanka]]n Newspaper at Internet on 23 September 2010[<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.colombopage.com/archive_10B/Sep23_1285222003KA.php|title = Sign language recognized in Sri Lanka|website = Colombo Page|date = 23 September 2010|location = Colombo, Sri Lanka}}</ref>]\n\n===Thailand===\n[[Thai Sign Language]] was acknowledged as \"the national language of deaf people in Thailand\" on 17 August 1999, in a resolution signed by the Permanent Secretary for Education on behalf of the Royal Thai Government that affirmed the rights of deaf people to learn this distinct sign language as their first language at home and in schools. According to a  [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231953/http://pr.gallaudet.edu/otg/BackIssues.asp?ID=3810 report by Charles Reilly (1999)], \"specific actions will be taken by the government, including hiring deaf people as teachers and instructors of sign language in deaf schools, and providing interpreters for deaf people in higher education.\"\n\n===Turkey===\nThere is currently{{when|date=April 2020}} no official recognition of the [[Turkish Sign Language]], the de facto sign language in use by the Turkish deaf community.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 1 July 2005, the [[Turkish Grand National Assembly]] enacted an updated [[disability discrimination act|Disability Law]] (No. 5378), which for the first time in Turkish law made references to sign language. Law no. 15 says that a sign language is to be used in the deaf education system, and law no. 30 says that sign language interpreting is to be provided to deaf people.<ref>http://majordomo.valenciacc.edu/hypermail/slling-l/0508/0013.html{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, these laws are yet to be implemented (as of 2007), and it remains to be seen what form of sign language, if any, will be supported. There has been some discussion in parliament about \"developing\" a standardised sign language.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abgs.gov.tr/tarama/tarama_files/19/SC19DET_People%20with%20disabilities.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2007-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070404073157/http://www.abgs.gov.tr/tarama/tarama_files/19/SC19DET_People%20with%20disabilities.pdf |archive-date=2007-04-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTurkey also has action plans for disability issues, such as the Employment of Disabled Persons Plan (2005\u20132010) and the Prevention of Discrimination Against Disabled Persons Plan (2006\u20132010).{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Uganda===\nOn 8 October 1995, [[Uganda]] adopted a new constitution that included a mention that 'The State shall [...] promote the development of a sign language for the deaf'.<ref>[[World Federation of the Deaf|WFD]] News, April 1996.</ref> It does not specify the [[Ugandan Sign Language]] as being the intented language. A Deaf signer, 27-year-old [[Alex Ndeezi]], was elected to [[Parliament of Uganda|parliament]] in 1996.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|XXIV (iii). The State shall [...] promote the development of a sign language for the deaf.\"|4=[http://www.parliament.go.ug/index.php?option=com_wrapper&Itemid=78 \"National Objectives and Directive Principles of State Policy\", Constitution of Uganda]}}\n\n===United States of America===\nThe Federal government does not recognize any language spoken or signed as an official language. However many individual states have laws recognizing [[American Sign Language]] as a \"foreign language\"; some recognize ASL as a language of instruction in schools.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} A number of U.S. universities accept ASL credit to fulfill foreign language requirements.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unm.edu/~wilcox/UNM/univlist.html |title=Universities That Accept ASL in Fulfillment of Foreign Language Requirements |publisher=University of New Mexico |last=Wilcox |first=Sherman}}</ref>\n\n===Uruguay===\n\nAlthough there are no \"official\" languages in Uruguay, nevertheless, Lengua de Se\u00f1as Uruguaya, or \"LSU\" (In English: \"Uruguayan Sign Language\"), was \"recognized\" as the language of deaf persons in 2001 by the law.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110704041632/http://200.40.229.134/IndexDB/Leyes/ConsultaLeyes.asp LEY No. 17.378.] ''Recon\u00f3cese a todos los efectos a la Lengua de Se\u00f1as Uruguaya como la lengua natural de las personas sordas y de sus comunidades en todo el territorio de la Rep\u00fablica.''  10 de Julio de 2001.  Parlamento del Uruguay.</ref>\n\nIn the 2008 law 18.437 (\"Ley General de Educaci\u00f3n. 12 de Diciembre de 2008\"), LSU is \"considered\" to be one of the mother tongues of Uruguayan citizens (along with Uruguayan Spanish and Uruguayan Portuguese. In the policy documents of the Comisi\u00f3n de Pol\u00edticas Ling\u00fc\u00edsticas en la Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica (the Public Education Language Policy Commission, which is part of the Administraci\u00f3n Nacional de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica, ANEP) it is proposed that LSU would be the principal language of deaf education.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Venezuela===\n[[Venezuelan Sign Language]] was recognised in the country's [[Constitution of Venezuela|constitution]] on 12 November 1999.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Zimbabwe===\nThe various [[Zimbabwean sign languages]], grouped together as \"sign language\", are recognised in the 2013 [[Constitution of Zimbabwe]] as one of the sixteen \"officially recognised languages of Zimbabwe\".<ref name=\"constitution\">\"The following languages, namely Chewa, Chibarwe, English, Kalanga, Koisan, Nambya, Ndau, Ndebele, Shangani, Shona, sign language, Sotho, Tonga, Tswana, Venda and Xhosa, are the officially recognised languages of Zimbabwe.\"  ([http://www.kubatana.net/docs/legisl/constitution_zim_draft_copac_130125.pdf Chapter 1, section 6, CONSTITUTION OF ZIMBABWE (final draft)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002110534/http://www.kubatana.net/docs/legisl/constitution_zim_draft_copac_130125.pdf |date=2013-10-02 }}).</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060216150733/http://fevlado.be/themas/gebarentaal/documenten/Status%20van%20gebarentalen%20in%20Europa.pdf Report on the status of Sign Languages in Europe] (PDF link)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050920061758/http://www.deafcouncil.org.uk/drcsub.htm Official Recognition of British Sign Language]\n\n{{sign language navigation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legal Recognition of Sign Languages}}\n[[Category:Sign language]]\n[[Category:Language policy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=April 2020}}\n\nThe '''legal recognition of sign languages''' differs widely. In some jurisdictions (countries, states, provinces or regions), a [[sign language]] is an official language, whereas in others it has a protected status in certain areas such as education. Governments sometimes stipulate in their constitutions or laws that 'sign language' is recognised or protected, but they fail to specify ''which'' sign language exactly, as there may be several different sign languages in common use within its borders, which has led to problems.\n\nExtending legal recognition is one of the major concerns of the international [[Deaf community]], however, symbolic recognition is no guarantee for an effective improvement of the life of sign language users, and it has been argued that sign languages should be recognized and supported not merely as an accommodation for the disabled, but as the communication medium of language communities.<ref>Sarah C. E. Batterbury. 2012. ''Language Policy'' 11:253\u2013272.</ref>\n\n==Sign language status by state==\n\n===Australia===\n[[Auslan]] was recognised by the Australian Government as a \"community language other than English\" and the preferred language of the Deaf community in policy statements in 1987 and 1991. This recognition does not ensure any provision of services in Auslan, but use of Auslan in Deaf education and provision of Auslan/English interpreters is becoming more common.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|It is now increasingly recognised that signing deaf people constitute a group like any other non-English speaking language group in Australia, with a distinct sub-culture recognised by shared history, social life and sense of identity, united and symbolised by fluency in Auslan, the principal means of communication within the Australian Deaf Community.|||Australia's Language: The Australian Language and Literacy Policy (page 20). (Australian Government Publishing Service, Canberra, 1991)}}\n\n===Austria===\n[[Austrian Sign Language]] (\u00d6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprache, \u00d6GS) was recognised by the Austrian Parliament in 2005. On 1 September 2005 the Austrian Constitution was amended to include a new article: \"\u00a78 (3) Die \u00d6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprache ist als eigenst\u00e4ndige Sprache anerkannt. Das N\u00e4here bestimmen die Gesetze.\u201c (\"Austrian Sign Language is recognised as independent language. The laws will determine the details.\")<ref>Krausneker, Verena (2005) \u00d6sterreichs erste Minderheitensprache, in: [https://web.archive.org/web/20070310204101/http://minderheiten.at/stimme/stimme56f.htmSTIMME von und f\u00fcr Minderheiten # 56]</ref><ref>Krausneker, Verena (2006) ''Taubstumm bis geb\u00e4rdensprachig. Die \u00f6sterreichische Geb\u00e4rdensprachgemeinschaft aus soziolinguistischer Perspektive.'' Verlag Drava.</ref>\n\n===Belgium===\n\n====French Community====\nThe [[Parliament of the French Community|Parliament]] of the [[French Community of Belgium]] recognised [[French Belgian Sign Language]] (LSFB) in a [[decree]] of October 2003. This recognition entails:\n# a cultural (symbolical) recognition and\n# the foundation of a commission that will advise the Government of the French Community in all matters related to LSFB.\n\nIn [https://web.archive.org/web/20041105050456/http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_officiel.pdf ''D\u00e9cret relatif \u00e0 la reconnaissance de la langue des signes''] (Decree on the recognition of the sign language), from three possible legal interpretations of the term 'recognition',<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_LS.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2006-05-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060927092446/http://www.ffsb.be/doc/LS/decret_LS.pdf#page=8 |archive-date=2006-09-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> the following one was retained: \"It concerns a symbolic recognition that goes hand in hand with a general measure, permitting every minister to take action in fields relative to his authority.\"<ref name=\"walloon\">\"... il s'agit d'une reconnaissance cadre assortie d'une mesure d'ex\u00e9cution g\u00e9n\u00e9rale permettant \u00e0 chaque ministre concern\u00e9 de prendre les arr\u00eat\u00e9s d'application relevant de ses comp\u00e9tences ...\"</ref>\n\n====Flemish Community====\n[[Flemish Sign Language]] was recognised on 2006-04-26 by the [[Flemish Parliament]]. This recognition entails:\n# a cultural (symbolical) recognition (see excerpt below),\n# the foundation of a commission that will advise the Flemish government in all matters related to VGT and\n# the structural funding of research and development of VGT.\nThis recognition was accelerated by the most successful petition ever with the Flemish Parliament and the presence of a Deaf member of parliament, Helga Stevens, and her interpreters in the Flemish Parliament.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|Cultural recognition entails that the Flemish Government recognises the Flemish Sign Language as the language of the Deaf Community in Flanders. This 'recognition' encompasses the following three meanings: (1) the Flemish Government acknowledges the correctness of the fact that the Flemish Sign Language is the language of the Deaf Community in Flanders, (2) the Flemish Government also accepts the existence of this language in the judicial domain and treats it accordingly and (3) the Flemish Government expresses its respect for this language.<ref name=\"flemish\">\"Die 'erkenning' omvat hierbij de drie betekennissen van het woord: (1) de Vlaamse overheid bevestigt de juistheid van het feit dat de Vlaamse Gebarentaal de taal is van de Dovengemeenschap in Vlaanderen, (2) de Vlaamse overheid aanvaardt het bestaan van die taal ook op juridisch vlak en behandelt ze als dustanig en (3) de Vlaamse overheid uit haar waardering voor deze taal.\"</ref>|||[http://jsp.vlaamsparlement.be/docs/stukken/2005-2006/g729-1.pdf Decreet houdende de erkenning van de Vlaamse Gebarentaal] (Decree on the recognition of the Flemish Sign Language)}}\n\n===Brazil===\nThe [[Brazilian Sign Language|Brazilian Sign Language (LIBRAS)]] was legally recognized in 2002 but can't replace written [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]];<ref name=\"Brazil 2002\">[http://planalto.gov.br/CCIVIL_03/LEIS/2002/L10436.htm , April 24, 2002].</ref> the law was [[regulation|regulated]] in 2005.<ref name=\"Brazil 2005\">[http://www.planalto.gov.br/ccivil_03/_ato2004-2006/2005/decreto/d5626.htm Brazilian decree n\u00ba 5626, December 22, 2005].</ref> The language must be taught as a part of the [[school of education|education]] and [[speech and language pathology]] curricula, and law also mandates that LIBRAS be an elective subject as part of every other undergraduate course. LIBRAS teachers, instructors and translators are recognized professionals. Schools and health services must provide access (\"[[inclusion (education)|include]]\") to deaf people.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Canada===\nThe [[Accessible Canada Act]], passed on 21 June 2019, recognised '[[American Sign Language]], [[Quebec Sign Language]] and Indigenous sign languages (...) as the primary languages for communication by deaf persons in Canada.'<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://laws.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/A-0.6/page-1.html |title=Accessible Canada Act S.C. 2019, c. 10 |publisher=Canadian Ministry of Justice |date=21 June 2019 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nQuestion Period in the [[House of Commons of Canada]] is interpreted in both [[Quebec Sign Language]] and [[American Sign Language]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} [[Section Fourteen of the Canadian Charter of Rights and Freedoms]] specifies that an accused person who does not understand the language in which his or her trial is carried out, or is deaf, is entitled to an interpreter.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn several of Canada's provinces ([[Manitoba]] in 1988, [[Alberta]] in 1990, [[Ontario]] in 1993), [[ASL]] is an officially recognised minority language with legally embedded rights.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOntario recognised ASL and LSQ as a language in which the Deaf can be taught when it altered its Education Act in 1993. Ontario formally recognised ASL in 2007 attributing to it the rights of fellow minority languages.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n[[Inuit Sign Language|Inuit or Inuktitut Sign Language]] (IUR) is used in Canada's arctic communities, and was developed locally by families and communities who found a need for their deaf families and community members. Deaf Inuit who have attended school in Canada's south have also learned ASL. IUR made its debut in Nunavut legislature in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/inuit-sign-language-makes-debut-in-nunavut-legislature-1.772092|title=Inuit sign language makes debut in Nunavut legislature - CBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Maritime Sign Language]] (MSL), which derives from the [[British Sign Language]], is a moribund sign language in Canada's [[The Maritimes|Maritime Provinces]].<ref name=CBC>{{cite news |first=Emma |last=Davie |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/preserving-maritime-sign-language-msl-deaf-community-1.5402328 |title=How the deaf community is preserving Maritime Sign Language |publisher=[[CBC News]] |date=31 December 2019}}</ref> It does not have any official recognition and is no longer instructed in schools, having been replaced by American Sign Language.<ref name=CBC/> The MSL-teaching [[Halifax School for the Deaf]] operated from 1856 to June 1961, after which the Interprovincial School for the Education of the Deaf (later renamed Atlantic Provinces Special Education Authority, APSEA) in [[Amherst, Nova Scotia]] took over until it closed in 1995.<ref name=CBC/><ref>{{Cite book |last=Marsh |first=James H. |date=1999 |title=The Canadian Encyclopedia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wR_-aSFyvuYC&pg=PA640 |location=Toronto, Ontario |publisher=McClelland & Stewart Inc. |page=640 |isbn=9780771020995 |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Chile===\nChilean Sign Language (LSCh), Chile enacted in Law No. 20,422, in 2010 in order to ensure the right to equality of opportunity for disabled people, negating any form of discrimination against them. And which recognizes sign language as the natural means of communication of the deaf community.<ref>[http://www.leychile.cl/Navegar?idLey=20422 Ley 20422 BCN LEGISLACI\u00d3N CHILENA, 2010]</ref>\n\n===Czech Republic===\n[[Czech Sign Language]] gained legal recognition as a human language with the passage of the Sign Language Law 155/1998 Sb (\"Z\u00e1kon o znakov\u00e9 \u0159e\u010di 155/1998 Sb\").<ref>{{in lang|cs}} {{cite web|url=http://www.sagit.cz/pages/sbirkatxt.asp?zdroj=sb98155&cd=76&typ=r |title=Z\u00c1KON ze dne 11. \u010dervna 1998 o znakov\u00e9 \u0159e\u010di a o zm\u011bn\u011b dal\u0161\u00edch z\u00e1kon\u016f - Sb\u00edrka z\u00e1kon\u016f - Nakladatelstv\u00ed Sagit, a.s |publisher=Sagit.cz |date=2000-12-01 |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\n===Denmark===\n\nAs of 13 May 2014, [[Danish Sign Language]] gained legal recognition. The Danish Parliament established The Danish Sign Language Council \"to devise principles and guidelines for the monitoring of the Danish sign language and offer advice and information on the Danish sign language.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dsn.dk/tegnsprog/about-the-danish-sign-language-council|title=The Danish Sign Language Council \u2014 Dansk Sprogn\u00e6vn|website=www.dsn.dk}}</ref>\n\n===European Union===\nThe [[European Parliament]] unanimously approved a resolution about Deaf Sign Languages on 17 June 1988 (available online here<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.policy.hu/flora/ressign2.htm |title=Published by: EUD |publisher=Policy.hu |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>). The resolution indirectly asks all member states for recognition of their sign languages as official languages of the Deaf.\n\n{{cquote|The European Parliament [...] calls on the Commission to make a proposal to the Council concerning official recognition of the sign language used by deaf people in each Member State.|||[http://www.policy.hu/flora/ressign2.htm European Parliament Resolution on Sign Languages 1988]}}\n\nThe EP issued another resolution in 1998 with more or less the same content as in 1988, (see RESOLUTION on sign languages for the deaf, Official Journal C 187, 18/07/1988 P. 0236 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CELEX:51987IP0302:EN:NOT |title=EUR-Lex - 51987IP0302 - EN - EUR-Lex |publisher=Eur-lex.europa.eu |date= |accessdate=2018-09-11}}</ref>\n\nA third resolution was passed in 2016, drafted by Helga Stevens MEP, Europe's first deaf female MEP, a lawyer, and former Executive Director and subsequent President of the European Union of the Deaf. This resolution is on \"Sign language and professional sign language interpreters\". The text in this resolution is more sophisticated than preceding European Parliamentary resolutions, demonstrating the expertise of the author and also the increased maturity of the communities working towards increased recognition of sign language (e.g. drawing on academic expertise in Deaf Studies, interpreting studies, linguistics, etc.)<ref>http://www.europarl.europa.eu/doceo/document/TA-8-2016-0442_EN.html</ref>\n\n===Finland===\n[[Finnish Sign Language]] was recognised in the constitution in August 1995.\n\n{{cquote|''Section 17 - Right to one's language and culture'' [...] The rights of persons using sign language and of persons in need of interpretation or translation aid owing to disability shall be guaranteed by an Act.<ref name=\"finnish\">17 \u00a7 Oikeus omaan kieleen ja kulttuuriin [...] Viittomakielt\u00e4 k\u00e4ytt\u00e4vien sek\u00e4 vammaisuuden vuoksi tulkitsemisja k\u00e4\u00e4nn\u00f6sapua tarvitsevien oikeudet turvataan lailla. (Ministry of Justice, Finland: [http://www.finlex.fi/linkit/ajansd/19990731000 ''Suomen perustuslaki''].)</ref>|||[http://www.om.fi/uploads/54begu60narbnv_1.pdf The Constitution of Finland]}}\n\n===Iceland===\n[[Icelandic Sign Language]] was recognised by law in education in 2004.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|This National Curriculum Guide contains, for the first time, provisions on special Icelandic instruction for students whose mother tongue is not Icelandic. There are also new provisions on special Icelandic instruction for deaf and hearing-impaired pupils and sign-language instruction for the deaf. The objectives for Icelandic instruction of immigrants and the deaf and of sign-language instruction fall under the subject area of language arts (Icelandic) in compulsory school. [...]\n\nSign language is of basic importance for the development of language, personality and thinking of deaf children. For the deaf, sign language is the most important source of knowledge and their route to participation in Icelandic culture and the culture of the deaf. Sign language is of great importance for all school work and for the pupils' life and work.<ref name=\"icelandic\">\u00cd a\u00f0aln\u00e1mskr\u00e1 grunnsk\u00f3la eru \u00ed fyrsta sinn sett \u00e1kv\u00e6\u00f0i um s\u00e9rstaka \u00edslenskukennslu fyrir nemendur me\u00f0 anna\u00f0 m\u00f3\u00f0urm\u00e1l en \u00edslensku. Einnig eru n\u00fd \u00e1kv\u00e6\u00f0i um s\u00e9rstaka \u00edslenskukennslu fyrir heyrnarlausa og heyrnarskerta nemendur og t\u00e1knm\u00e1lskennslu fyrir heyrnarlausa. Markmi\u00f0 fyrir \u00edslenskukennslu n\u00fdb\u00faa og heyrnarlausra og t\u00e1knm\u00e1lskennslu falla undir n\u00e1mssvi\u00f0 \u00edslensku \u00ed grunnsk\u00f3la. [...]\n\nT\u00e1knm\u00e1l hefur grundvallar\u00fe\u00fd\u00f0ingu fyrir \u00feroska m\u00e1ls, pers\u00f3nuleika og hugsunar heyrnarlausra nemenda. Hj\u00e1 heyrnarlausum er t\u00e1knm\u00e1li\u00f0 mikilv\u00e6gasta uppspretta \u00feekkingar og lei\u00f0 til a\u00f0 taka \u00fe\u00e1tt \u00ed \u00edslenskri menningu og menningu heyrnarlausra. T\u00e1knm\u00e1li\u00f0 hefur mikla \u00fe\u00fd\u00f0ingu fyrir alla vinnu \u00ed sk\u00f3lanum og fyrir l\u00edf og starf nemendanna. (Ministry of Education, Science and Culture: [http://bella.stjr.is/utgafur/AGalmennurhluti.pdf ''A\u00f0aln\u00e1mskr\u00e1 grunnsk\u00f3la: Almennur hluti''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927194051/http://bella.stjr.is/utgafur/AGalmennurhluti.pdf |date=2007-09-27 }})</ref>|||4=[http://bella.mrn.stjr.is/utgafur/general.pdf#page=23 The National Curriculum Guide for Compulsory School (Ministry of Education, Science and Culture, 2004)] (official translation)}}\n\nOn 27 May 2011, the Icelandic Parliament unanimously approved a bill which recognises Icelandic Sign Language as an official minority language with constitutional rights and as the first language of the deaf people of [[Iceland]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Indian subcontinent===\nThere is no official recognition of [[Indo-Pakistani Sign Language]] (IPSL), which is well-documented, widely used throughout the [[Indian subcontinent]] across national and state borders with few regional variations, and has over a million estimated users in [[India]] alone, is also commonly used in [[Pakistan]] and probably also in [[Bangladesh]].<ref>{{Cite book |last=Evans |first=Nicholas |title=Reciprocals and Semantic Typology |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U020QQv1Qn4C&pg=PA95 |location=Amsterdam & Philadelphia |publisher=John Benjamins Publishing |page=95 |isbn=9789027206794 |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Ireland===\nIrish Sign Language was given official recognition in 2017. The \"Recognition of Irish Sign Language for the Deaf Community Bill 2016\" passed all stages in the [[Oireachtas]] (Irish Parliament) on 14 December 2017, and was signed into law by the [[President of Ireland]] [[Michael D. Higgins|Michael D Higgins]] on 24 December 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/irish-sign-language-given-official-legal-recognition-1.3338081|title=Irish Sign Language given official legal recognition|work=The Irish Times|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/ireland/2017/1224/929482-sign-language-bill/|title=President signs Irish Sign Language bill into law|date=2017-12-24|work=RTE.ie|access-date=2018-01-16|language=en}}</ref> Prior to 2017, there was no automatic right for deaf people to have an ISL [[Language interpretation|interpreter]] (except for criminal court proceedings). For the deaf community, recognition of ISL means more legal rights and better access to [[public service]]s - including [[Education in the Republic of Ireland|education]], [[Healthcare in the Republic of Ireland|healthcare]], [[Media of the Republic of Ireland|media]] and [[banking]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/2017/1213/927259-irish-sign-language/|title=D\u00e1il passes 'historic' sign language legislation|date=2017-12-14|work=RTE.ie|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/irish-sign-language-set-to-be-given-official-status-36407921.html|title=Irish Sign Language set to be given official status - Independent.ie|work=Independent.ie|access-date=2017-12-14|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.breakingnews.ie/ireland/irish-sign-language-set-to-receive-official-recognition-818648.html|title=Irish sign language set to receive official recognition|date=2017-12-14|work=Breaking News|access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref>\n\n===Italy===\nThere is no official recognition of [[Italian Sign Language]] (''Lingua dei Segni Italiana'', LIS) yet. Those who oppose LIS recognition say this language is \"grammarless,\" although, by definition, a [[Language#The properties of language|language]] cannot be, in fact, grammarless. Several research on the matter have already shown that [[Italian Sign Language]] is a proper language.<ref>[http://michelebrunelli.interfree.it/GrammLIS_e_Restrittive.pdf Michele Brunelli: Grammatica della LIS] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722035622/http://michelebrunelli.interfree.it/GrammLIS_e_Restrittive.pdf |date=2011-07-22 }}</ref>\n\n===Kenya===\nThe 2010 [[Constitution of Kenya]] recognises [[Kenyan Sign Language]] and states that the state shall promote the development and use of Kenyan Sign Language (Article 7.3b). Sign language is recognised further in Article 120 (1) which states that 'the official languages of Parliament are [[Swahili language|Kiswahili]], [[English language|English]] and Kenyan Sign Language and the business of Parliament may be conducted in English, Kiswahili and Kenyan Sign Language.'<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://kenyalaw.org:8181/exist/kenyalex/actview.xql?actid=Const2010 |title=Constitution of Kenya, 2010 |work=Kenya Law |publisher=Judiciary of Kenya |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Malta ===\nThe [[Maltese Sign Language]] (LSM) was official recognized by parliament in March 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maltatoday.com.mt/news/national/63266/parliament_gives_maltese_sign_language_official_recognition|title=Parliament gives Maltese sign language official recognition}}</ref>\n\n=== Mexico ===\n\nThe [[Mexican Sign Language]] (LSM) was officially declared a \"national language\" in 2003, and it started being used in public deaf education thereafter.<ref>Ley Federal para las Personas con Discapacidad.  http://www.diputados.gob.mx/LeyesBiblio/pdf/262.pdf {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150616003344/http://www.diputados.gob.mx/LeyesBiblio/pdf/262.pdf |date=2015-06-16 }}</ref> Before 2003, deaf education in the country was focused on oralism (speech and lipreading) with few schools conducting classes in LSM.<ref>Karla Faurot, Dianne Dellinger, Andy Eatough, Steve Parkhurst (1992, revised 1998 and 2001) The identity of Mexican sign as a language. http://www.sil.org/silesr/2000/2000-002/ \u00a9 1999 Summer Institute of Linguistics.</ref>\n\n===Nepal===\nAlthough [[Nepali Sign Language]] has not yet been officially recognized as the [[mother tongue]] of Nepal's deaf population, legislation is underway which will bring Nepali law in line with the provisions of the UN [[Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities]]. These laws will recognize the rights of the deaf to use [[Nepali Sign Language]] have it used in education, in social life, in the legal sphere, etc., and this should thus lead to official governmental recognition of [[Nepali Sign Language]] on a par with the various spoken languages of Nepal.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Netherlands===\n[[File:Nederlandse gebarentaal krijgt eindelijk een zichtbare plek in onze samenleving.webm|thumb|[[Roelof van Laar]] explaining the 2016 bill to recognise NGT]]\nThe [[Dutch Sign Language]] (NGT) has not been recognised officially by law. In 2010, the [[Christian Union (Netherlands)|Christian Union]] party introduced a bill to recognise NGT, but it did not pass.<ref name=\"AD2016\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.ad.nl/nieuws/erken-nederlandse-gebarentaal-als-officiele-taal~a5a253f6/ |title=Erken Nederlandse gebarentaal als offici\u00eble taal |publisher=Algemeen Dagblad |date=3 October 2016 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref>\nIn October 2016, this was followed by a bill from MPs [[Roelof van Laar]] ([[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour Party]]) and [[Carla Dik-Faber]] (Christian Union) for legal recognition of NGT as an official language.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2016/10/03/gebarentaal-moet-erkend-worden-als-officiele-taal-a1524573|title=PvdA en CU: erken gebarentaal als offici\u00eble taal|author=Beila Heilbron|publisher=NRC Handelsblad|date=3 October 2016 |language=nl}}</ref> After Van Laar's departure, MP [[Attje Kuiken]] (Labour Party) took over the bill in September 2019, while MP [[Jessica van Eijs]] ([[Democrats 66]]) joined Kuiken and Dik-Faber.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.eerstekamer.nl/behandeling/20190927/brief_lid_fractie_brief_van_de/document3/f=/vl29hrq7v1yn.pdf |title=Voorstel van wet van de leden Van Laar en Dik-Faber ter erkenning van Nederlandse gebarentaal (Wet erkenning Nederlandse gebarentaal) |author=Attje Kuiken & Carla Dik-Faber |work=Brief van de leden Kuiken en Dik-Faber |publisher=Senate of the Netherlands |date=27 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://nos.nl/nieuwsuur/artikel/2300498-initiatiefwet-nederlandse-gebarentaal-erkennen-als-officiele-taal.html |title=Initiatiefwet: Nederlandse Gebarentaal erkennen als offici\u00eble taal |author=Linda de Groot |work=Nieuwsuur |publisher=NOS |date=5 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref> At the end of September 2019 the Advisory Division of the [[Council of State (Netherlands)|Council of State]] stated that the text of the bill was still too vague, as it did not make clear which problems it exactly intended to address and through which practical means; for example, it asked whether 'the Deaf culture' \u2013 mentioned in the bill \u2013 also needed to be legally recognised, and if so, what that term precisely entailed.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.raadvanstate.nl/@117458/samenvatting-gebarentaal/ |title=Samenvatting advies initiatiefwetsvoorstel erkenning Nederlandse gebarentaal |publisher=Advisory Division of the Council of State |date=30 September 2019 |accessdate=17 April 2020 |language=nl}}</ref>\n\n===New Zealand===\n[[New Zealand Sign Language]] became the third official language of [[New Zealand]] in April 2006, joining [[M\u0101ori language|English and M\u0101ori]] when the bill was passed in the New Zealand Parliament on 6 April 2006.<ref>McKee, R. 2007. The eyes have it! Our third official language\u2013New Zealand Sign Language. ''Journal of New Zealand Studies'', NS 4-5.129-148.</ref>\n\n{{cquote|Part 2 cl 6: New Zealand Sign Language is declared to be an official language of New Zealand.|||[http://www.odi.govt.nz/documents/nzds/nzsl-bill.pdf New Zealand Sign Language Bill]}}\n\n=== North Macedonia ===\nThe [[Macedonian Sign Language]] (''\u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043d \u0458\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, Makedonski znakoven jazik'') is officially recognized as a \"natural way of communication between the people\". The language is regulated by a law, which allows students and every individual in [[North Macedonia]] to study the language. Also, the law secures the right of the interpreter for the students with special needs, and every other deaf person can request an interpreter, as well.<ref name=\"\u0437\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d\">''[http://www.deafmkd.org.mk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=57&Itemid=82&lang=mk \u0417\u0430\u043a\u043e\u043d \u0437\u0430 \u0443\u043f\u043e\u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0430 \u043d\u0430  \u0437\u043d\u0430\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043e\u0442 \u0458\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0421\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0435\u043d \u0432\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043d\u0430 \u0420\u0435\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0458\u0430, \u0431\u0440\u043e\u0458 105, 21 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442 2009, \u0421\u043a\u043e\u043f\u0458\u0435]''</ref> Currently,{{when|date=April 2020}} there are more than 6.000 Macedonian citizens with deafness.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Northern Ireland===\nIn Northern Ireland, both [[British Sign Language]] and [[Irish Sign Language]] (but not [[Northern Ireland Sign Language]]) were recognised as official languages by the [[Northern Ireland Office]] in 2004,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nio.gov.uk/paul-murphy-announces-recognition-for-sign-language/media-detail.htm?newsID=8540 |title=Paul Murphy announces recognition for sign language |accessdate=2008-06-22 |date=2004-03-30 |publisher=[[Northern Ireland Office]] |quote=I am pleased to announce formal recognition for both British and Irish Sign Languages in Northern Ireland. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520115301/http://www.nio.gov.uk/paul-murphy-announces-recognition-for-sign-language/media-detail.htm?newsID=8540 |archivedate=2011-05-20 }}</ref> but they don't yet have the same status as the province's two official minority languages, [[Irish language|Irish]] and [[Ulster Scots language|Ulster-Scots]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Norway===\n[[Norwegian Sign Language]] is recognised by law in education.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Papua New Guinea===\nIn May 2015, [[Papua New Guinean Sign Language]] became the fourth official language of [[Papua New Guinea]].<ref name=\"sil.org\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sil.org/about/news/two-sign-languages-given-official-language-status|title=Two Sign Languages Given Official Language Status|date=23 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Philippines ===\nArticle 3 of Republic Act No. 11106 declared [[Filipino Sign Language]] as the national sign language of the [[Philippines]], specifying that it shall be recognized, supported and promoted as the medium of official communication in all transactions involving the deaf, and as the language of instruction of deaf education.<ref>{{cite act |url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/downloads/2018/10oct/20181030-RA-11106-RRD.pdf|title=The Filipino Sign Language Act|type=Republic act|number=11106|article=3|work=Official Gazette |publisher=Government of the Philippines|date=30 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Genalyn Kabiling |work=Manila Bulletin |title=Filipino Sign Language declared as nat\u2019l sign language of Filipino deaf |date=12 November 2018 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2018/11/12/filipino-sign-language-declared-as-natl-sign-language-of-filipino-deaf/ |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Portugal===\n{{cquote|Art. 74, 2 (h): In implementing the education policy, the state shall be charged with protecting and developing Portuguese sign language, as an expression of culture and an instrument for access to education and equal opportunities.<ref name=\"portuguese\">Na realiza\u00e7\u00e3o da pol\u00edtica de ensino incumbe ao Estado proteger e valorizar a l\u00edngua gestual portuguesa, enquanto express\u00e3o cultural e instrumento de acesso \u00e0 educa\u00e7\u00e3o e da igualdade de oportunidades. (Assembleia da Rep\u00fablica: [http://www.parlamento.pt/const_leg/crp_port/index.html Constitui\u00e7\u00e3o da rep\u00fablica portuguesa] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070809203630/http://www.parlamento.pt/const_leg/crp_port/index.html |date=2007-08-09 }}</ref>|||[http://www.parlamento.pt/ingles/cons_leg/crp_ing/ Constitution of Portugal]}}\nAs an example, many shows (such as the news) in public channels ([[R\u00e1dio e Televis\u00e3o de Portugal|RTP]]) have one corner of the screen with a person translating what's being said into sign language.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\n===Russia===\nRussian Sign Language (''\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0436\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u044f\u0437\u044b\u043a'') has very limited legal recognition. In accordance with the Federal \"Law on Protection of People with Disabilities\" the sign language is considered a language used for inter-personal communication only, which means that no state support for the language is provided.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}}\n\n=== Slovak Republic ===\n[[Slovak Sign Language]] was recognised in 1995 by law: \"Z\u00e1kon o posunkovej re\u010di nepo\u010duj\u00facich os\u00f4b 149/1995 Sb\" - the Law of the Sign Language of the Deaf 149/1995.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== South Africa ===\n[[South African Sign Language]] is not specifically recognised as a [[Languages of South Africa|Language of South Africa]] by the country's [[Constitution of South Africa|constitution]], instead it contains the phrase \"sign language\" in the generic sense.<ref>http://www.info.gov.za/documents/constitution/1996/96cons1.htm#6 {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629092124/http://www.info.gov.za/documents/constitution/1996/96cons1.htm |date=2011-06-29 }}</ref>\nThere is a process underway in parliament to investigate the possibility of upgrading the status of SASL to become the country's 12th official language.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.pmg.org.za/report/20091113-language-issues-proposed-recognition-south-african-sign-language-offi |title=Archived copy |access-date=2010-10-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100515104619/http://www.pmg.org.za/report/20091113-language-issues-proposed-recognition-south-african-sign-language-offi |archive-date=2010-05-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=== South Korea ===\nOn 31 December 2015, the \"South Korean National Assembly passed legislation to recognize Korean Sign Language as one of Korea\u2019s official languages.\"<ref name=\"sil.org\"/>\n\n=== Spain ===\nOn 28 June 2007, Spanish and Catalan Sign Languages were recognised by the Spanish Parliament to be official languages in Spain. This recent legal development has opened a door to reinforced communication in the areas of healthcare, justice, education and MCM.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nSo far, the [[Autonomous communities of Spain|Autonomous Communities]] of [[Catalonia]], [[Andalusia]], and [[Valencia (autonomous community)|Valencia]] had granted the use of sign languages to the Deaf. In the other Spanish regions no sign languages were so far recognised, and support in terms of sign language interpretation for Deaf persons has been minimal or confined by different budgets. As pointed out, there are three sign languages claimed by Deaf organisations: [[Spanish Sign Language]], [[Catalan Sign Language]] (LSC) and [[Valencian Sign Language]] (LSPV), although some linguists consider these to be the same.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Catalonia====\nAlthough a regional law guarantees the presence of [[Catalan Sign Language]] since 1994 in all areas under the Catalan Government, such as education and media, until recently it was officially recognised the LSC in the [[Statute of Autonomy of Catalonia]] of 2006.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Andalusia====\nThe legal situation in Andalusia is similar to the one in Catalonia, where a regional Law guarantees the presence of the [[Spanish Sign Language]] (LSE) in all social scopes since 1998. Recently, a recognition of it is included in the reforming of their Statute of Autonomy. At the moment, Andalusia is the unique Community where LSE is recognised with regards to the rest of Spain. In any case, in linguistic terms, the LSE used there has a strong dialectal variation.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n====Valencia====\nUntil recently, Valencia had poor legal support for the Deaf. The approved 2006 Statute of Autonomy grants to Valencian Deaf their right to use [[Valencian Sign Language]] (LSPV or LSCV). (Though the statute refers only to \"sign language\" in a generic sense.){{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|Article 13,4: The Generalitat shall grant the use of the own sign language of deaf persons, which shall have to be purposed in education, protection and respect.<ref name=\"valencian\">La Generalitat garantir\u00e0 l\u2019\u00fas de la llengua de signes pr\u00f2pia de les persones sordes, que haur\u00e0 de ser objecte d\u2019ensenyament, protecci\u00f3 i respecte. (Corts Valencianes: [http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf Estatut d'Autonomia de la Communitat Valenciana] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926130504/http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf |date=2007-09-26 }}.)</ref>|||[http://www.cortsvalencianes.es/descarga/destacados/ESTATUT.pdf Statute of Autonomy of the Valencian Country]}}\n\n====Galicia====\n[[Galicia (Spain)|Galicia]] is said{{by whom|date=June 2012}} to be working on a bill concerning the recognition of a sign language.{{citation needed|date=June 2012}}\n\n=== Sri Lanka ===\nThe recognition of [[Sri Lankan sign languages|Sri Lankan Sign Language]] was accepted by [[Sri Lanka]] on 26 September 2010. According to the report by [[Sri Lanka]]n Newspaper at Internet on 23 September 2010[<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.colombopage.com/archive_10B/Sep23_1285222003KA.php|title = Sign language recognized in Sri Lanka|website = Colombo Page|date = 23 September 2010|location = Colombo, Sri Lanka}}</ref>]\n\n===Thailand===\n[[Thai Sign Language]] was acknowledged as \"the national language of deaf people in Thailand\" on 17 August 1999, in a resolution signed by the Permanent Secretary for Education on behalf of the Royal Thai Government that affirmed the rights of deaf people to learn this distinct sign language as their first language at home and in schools. According to a  [https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231953/http://pr.gallaudet.edu/otg/BackIssues.asp?ID=3810 report by Charles Reilly (1999)], \"specific actions will be taken by the government, including hiring deaf people as teachers and instructors of sign language in deaf schools, and providing interpreters for deaf people in higher education.\"\n\n===Turkey===\nThere is currently{{when|date=April 2020}} no official recognition of the [[Turkish Sign Language]], the de facto sign language in use by the Turkish deaf community.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn 1 July 2005, the [[Turkish Grand National Assembly]] enacted an updated [[disability discrimination act|Disability Law]] (No. 5378), which for the first time in Turkish law made references to sign language. Law no. 15 says that a sign language is to be used in the deaf education system, and law no. 30 says that sign language interpreting is to be provided to deaf people.<ref>http://majordomo.valenciacc.edu/hypermail/slling-l/0508/0013.html{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, these laws are yet to be implemented (as of 2007), and it remains to be seen what form of sign language, if any, will be supported. There has been some discussion in parliament about \"developing\" a standardised sign language.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.abgs.gov.tr/tarama/tarama_files/19/SC19DET_People%20with%20disabilities.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=2007-03-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070404073157/http://www.abgs.gov.tr/tarama/tarama_files/19/SC19DET_People%20with%20disabilities.pdf |archive-date=2007-04-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTurkey also has action plans for disability issues, such as the Employment of Disabled Persons Plan (2005\u20132010) and the Prevention of Discrimination Against Disabled Persons Plan (2006\u20132010).{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Uganda===\nOn 8 October 1995, [[Uganda]] adopted a new constitution that included a mention that 'The State shall [...] promote the development of a sign language for the deaf'.<ref>[[World Federation of the Deaf|WFD]] News, April 1996.</ref> It does not specify the [[Ugandan Sign Language]] as being the intented language. A Deaf signer, 27-year-old [[Alex Ndeezi]], was elected to [[Parliament of Uganda|parliament]] in 1996.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{cquote|XXIV (iii). The State shall [...] promote the development of a sign language for the deaf.\"|4=[http://www.parliament.go.ug/index.php?option=com_wrapper&Itemid=78 \"National Objectives and Directive Principles of State Policy\", Constitution of Uganda]}}\n\n===United States of America===\nThe Federal government does not recognize any language spoken or signed as an official language. However many individual states have laws recognizing [[American Sign Language]] as a \"foreign language\"; some recognize ASL as a language of instruction in schools.{{citation needed|date=November 2011}} A number of U.S. universities accept ASL credit to fulfill foreign language requirements.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unm.edu/~wilcox/UNM/univlist.html |title=Universities That Accept ASL in Fulfillment of Foreign Language Requirements |publisher=University of New Mexico |last=Wilcox |first=Sherman}}</ref>\n\n===Uruguay===\n\nAlthough there are no \"official\" languages in Uruguay, nevertheless, Lengua de Se\u00f1as Uruguaya, or \"LSU\" (In English: \"Uruguayan Sign Language\"), was \"recognized\" as the language of deaf persons in 2001 by the law.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110704041632/http://200.40.229.134/IndexDB/Leyes/ConsultaLeyes.asp LEY No. 17.378.] ''Recon\u00f3cese a todos los efectos a la Lengua de Se\u00f1as Uruguaya como la lengua natural de las personas sordas y de sus comunidades en todo el territorio de la Rep\u00fablica.''  10 de Julio de 2001.  Parlamento del Uruguay.</ref>\n\nIn the 2008 law 18.437 (\"Ley General de Educaci\u00f3n. 12 de Diciembre de 2008\"), LSU is \"considered\" to be one of the mother tongues of Uruguayan citizens (along with Uruguayan Spanish and Uruguayan Portuguese. In the policy documents of the Comisi\u00f3n de Pol\u00edticas Ling\u00fc\u00edsticas en la Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica (the Public Education Language Policy Commission, which is part of the Administraci\u00f3n Nacional de Educaci\u00f3n P\u00fablica, ANEP) it is proposed that LSU would be the principal language of deaf education.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Venezuela===\n[[Venezuelan Sign Language]] was recognised in the country's [[Constitution of Venezuela|constitution]] on 12 November 1999.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Zimbabwe===\nThe various [[Zimbabwean sign languages]], grouped together as \"sign language\", are recognised in the 2013 [[Constitution of Zimbabwe]] as one of the sixteen \"officially recognised languages of Zimbabwe\".<ref name=\"constitution\">\"The following languages, namely Chewa, Chibarwe, English, Kalanga, Koisan, Nambya, Ndau, Ndebele, Shangani, Shona, sign language, Sotho, Tonga, Tswana, Venda and Xhosa, are the officially recognised languages of Zimbabwe.\"  ([http://www.kubatana.net/docs/legisl/constitution_zim_draft_copac_130125.pdf Chapter 1, section 6, CONSTITUTION OF ZIMBABWE (final draft)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002110534/http://www.kubatana.net/docs/legisl/constitution_zim_draft_copac_130125.pdf |date=2013-10-02 }}).</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060216150733/http://fevlado.be/themas/gebarentaal/documenten/Status%20van%20gebarentalen%20in%20Europa.pdf Report on the status of Sign Languages in Europe] (PDF link)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050920061758/http://www.deafcouncil.org.uk/drcsub.htm Official Recognition of British Sign Language]\n\n{{sign language navigation}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Legal Recognition of Sign Languages}}\n[[Category:Sign language]]\n[[Category:Language policy]]\n", "name_user": "Chirag.Saluja", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed wordy sentence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Legal_recognition_of_sign_languages"}
{"title_page": "Toonami", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Zoonami|Tsunami|}}\n{{Short description|TV programming block, mostly animation}}\n{{Infobox programming block\n| name      = Toonami<!-- The current incarnation that began in 2012 -->\n| image     = [[File:Toonami logo 2019.png|250px]]<!-- WARNING: Please follow Wikipedia's logos of pictures. any deleted pictures will be reverted! -->\n| premiered = {{Start date and age|2012|5|26}}\n| closed    =\n| channel   = [[Adult Swim]]\n| country   = United States\n| headquarters = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| format    = [[Anime]] and [[Action film|action]] [[animation]]\n| runtime   = 3 hours\n| voices    = {{plainlist|\n* [[Sonny Strait]] <small>(1999\u20132000, 2015)</small>\n* [[Steven Blum]] <small>(2000\u20132008, 2012\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Dana Swanson]] <small>(2013\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Beau Billingslea]] <small>(2019)</small>}}\n| website   = [https://www.adultswim.com/toonami/ Toonami.com]\n}}\n\n'''Toonami''' ({{IPAc-en|t|u\u02d0|\u02c8|n|\u0251\u02d0|m|i}} {{respell|too|NAH|mee}}) is an American television [[Block programming|programming block]] that primarily broadcasts [[Japan]]ese [[anime]] and [[United States|American]] [[Action film|action]] [[animation]]. It was created by Sean Akins and Jason DeMarco and produced by [[Williams Street]], a division of [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Entertainment]]. The name is a [[portmanteau]] of the words \"[[cartoon]]\" and \"[[tsunami]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.tvguide.com/news/tsunami-wake-episodes-36301/|title = Tsunami's Wake Pulls Episodes|work = [[TV Guide]]|last1 = Fretts|first1 = Bruce|date = 2005-01-19|accessdate = 2018-05-17}}</ref> It currently broadcasts every Saturday night from 12 a.m. to 3 a.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|ET]]/[[Pacific Time Zone|PT]].\n\nToonami initially ran as an afternoon and evening block on [[Cartoon Network]] and was primarily aimed at boys aged 9\u201314. In its original run from 1997 to 2008, the block was known for showcasing action genre anime that became widely popular with American audiences. Toonami is recognized for its distinctive space-themed backdrop, [[anime music video]]s, [[drum and bass]]-flavored soundtrack, and robot host T.O.M. (short for Toonami Operations Module).\n\nOn May 26, 2012, Toonami was relaunched as a block on [[Adult Swim]]. The current incarnation is a rebrand of Adult Swim's Saturday night action block (itself inherited from Toonami's ''Midnight Run'' block), which primarily airs mature Japanese animation.\n\n\n==Broadcast History==\n{{OriginalResearch|section}}\n===Cartoon Network (1997\u20132008)===\n{{Infobox programming block\n| name      = Toonami<br />(Cartoon Network)\n| premiered = {{Start date and age|1997|03|17}}\n| closed    = {{End date and age|2008|9|20}}\n| owner     = [[WarnerMedia|Time Warner]] (through [[Turner Broadcasting System]])\n| channel   = [[Cartoon Network]] <small>(1997\u20132008)</small><br />[[Kids' WB]] <small>(2001\u20132002)</small>\n| country   = United States\n| headquarters = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| format    = [[Anime]] and [[Action film|action]] [[animation]]\n| voices    = {{plainlist|\n* [[C. Martin Croker]] <small>(1997\u20131999)</small>\n* [[Sonny Strait]] <small>(1999\u20132000)</small>\n* [[Steven Blum]] <small>(2000\u20132008)</small>\n* [[Sally Timms]] <small> (2000\u20132007)</small>\n* [[Khary Payton]] <small>(2002)</small>\n* [[Samantha Robson]] <small> (2004\u20132007) </small>\n* [[Dave Wittenberg]] <small>(2007\u20132008)</small>\n* [[Tom Kenny]] <small>(2007\u20132008)</small>}}\n| website   = {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/toonami |date=* |title=Archived official website}}\n}}\n\n====1997\u20131999: Moltar era====\nToonami was [[Cartoon Network]]'s primary action-animation block. The block premiered on March 17, 1997. It initially replaced Power Zone, Cartoon Network's most recent incarnation of the Super Adventures block, which had been a staple on the network since its debut on October 1, 1992. Toonami was originally a weekday afternoon cartoon and action block hosted by ''[[Space Ghost (TV series)|Space Ghost]]'' villain-turned-producer [[Moltar]] (voiced by [[C. Martin Croker]]) at the Ghost Planet Industries building from 1997 to July 9, 1999.\n\n====1999\u20132000: T.O.M. 1 era====\nOn Saturday, July 10, 1999, Cartoon Network relaunched Toonami with a new environment, the Ghost Planet Spaceship ''Absolution'', and a new host named T.O.M. (voiced by [[Sonny Strait]]), which introduced viewers to him with this speech:\n{{cquote|So it's a brand new Toonami, but the mission objectives remain the same. My name is TOM. I'm the new Moltar. Welcome aboard the Ghost Planet Spaceship Absolution, Cartoon Network's first and only interstellar broadcast and exploration vehicle. I'll give you the tour later. From this day forward she is completely responsible for all Toonami transmissions. I'm taking you guys into the new millennium! No big changes now, same show, same attitude; new place to do it, new guy to do it with. I'm not going to waste any more time, let's get back into it. Later.}}\n\nAlso introduced that day was the Midnight Run, a late night block. It was originally a five-hour Saturday night block (technically Sunday) at midnight EST until March 2000, when it moved to weeknights in an hour-long format until January 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/19991117093658/http://cartoonnetwork.com/favorites/toonami/index.html|title=Data Screen|accessdate=November 2, 2016|publisher=cartoonnetwork.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021201080928/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com:80/toonami/watch/tv_shows/ggundam/index.html|title=Tune in: Weekday Afternoons 5.0-7.0 P.M. (E/P)|date=December 1, 2002|accessdate=March 21, 2018|publisher=cartoonnetwork.com}}</ref> It consisted of anime such as ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'', ''[[Sailor Moon]]'', ''[[Voltron (1984 TV series)|Voltron]]'', ''[[Robotech (TV series)|Robotech]]'', ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam Wing]]'', and ''[[Outlaw Star]]''. Midnight Run tended to have more blood and violence than its daytime counterpart, even running an uncut version of ''Gundam Wing'' between March and November 2000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pope|first=Kyle|title=* Edit List Special - Cartoon Network Interview|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/edit-list/2002-03-04/cartoon-network-interview|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 2, 2012|date=March 4, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010306023529/http://www.animenewsservice.com/archives/feb22.htm|title=Gundam Wing Uncut To Air On Weeknights|date=March 6, 2000|accessdate=December 14, 2014|publisher=animenewsservice.com}}</ref> One special edition that started on Friday, August 31, 2001, featured music videos such as \u201c[[Clint Eastwood (song)|Clint Eastwood]]\u201d by [[Gorillaz]], and songs by [[Daft Punk]] from their 2001 album [[Discovery (Daft Punk album)|Discovery]], the music videos of which constitute the 2003 Japanese-French musical [[Interstella 5555]], and Kenna's \"Hellbent\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daft Punk Music Videos on Toonami.com|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2001-08-16/daft-punk-music-videos-on-toonami.com|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 2, 2012|date=August 16, 2001}}</ref> Another event was ''Dragon Ball Z'' taking over the Midnight Run for a week starting on March 26\u201330, 2001.\n\nStarting in September 2000, Toonami presented special interactive events known as Total Immersion Events (TIEs). These TIEs took place both on-air during Toonami and online at the official site, Toonami.com, and always occurred the week that the block's most popular series, ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Toonami Ratings Continue to Rise|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2001-03-21/toonami-ratings-continue-to-rise|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012|date=March 31, 2001}}</ref> returned for a new season. The first TIE was ''The Intruder'', which introduced T.O.M.'s companion, an [[Artificial intelligence|AI]] matrix known as Sara (voiced by country singer \"Cowboy\" [[Sally Timms]].) ''The Intruder'' was an eight episode mini-series that aired during Toonami from September 18\u201322, 2000. It involved the Absolution being attacked by an alien blob known only as \"the Intruder\", which ultimately devoured T.O.M.\n\n====2000\u20132003: T.O.M. 2 era====\n[[File:Toonami logo.svg|thumb|250px|Toonami logo used from February 21, 2000 to March 14, 2003; revived in 2017 for its 20th anniversary]]\nThough ''The Intruder'' resulted in the destruction of T.O.M., he was soon after upgraded by S.A.R.A. from a short [[Bomberman]]-esque character to a taller, sleeker, deeper-voiced incarnation dubbed T.O.M. 2 (voiced by [[Steven Blum]], who has since been the voice of all subsequent incarnations of the character).\n\nA Saturday morning incarnation, Toonami Rising Sun, ran from 2000 to 2001 at 9:00&nbsp;am to noon. It later ran from 10:00&nbsp;am to 1:00&nbsp;pm, then 11:00&nbsp;am to 1:00&nbsp;pm. This block was somewhat hampered to avoid competing with sister network Kids' WB.\n\nFrom July 30, 2001, until June 28, 2002, [[Kids' WB]] (also owned by [[WarnerMedia|Time Warner]]) aired a Toonami block that was, more or less, the Kids' WB lineup with the Toonami name. It was critically panned by industry observers, who noticed that the action branding of the block - which had added shows such as ''[[Generation O!]]'', ''[[Scooby-Doo]]'', and ''[[The Nightmare Room]]'', a live-action series created by ''[[Goosebumps]]'' author [[R. L. Stine]] - did not translate content-wise. In spring 2002, Kids' WB announced that they would drop the Toonami name from their weekday lineup, once again making the Toonami brand exclusive to Cartoon Network.\n\nThe TIE, ''Lockdown'', aired between September 17\u201321, 2001, and included the introduction of [[CartoonNetwork.com#Online|CartoonNetwork.com's]] first [[Massively multiplayer online role-playing game|MMORPG]], as well as a record-breaking amount of page views and ratings for the network.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cartoon Network Breaks Rating Records in 2001|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2002-03-11/cartoon-network-breaks-rating-records-in-2001|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012|date=March 11, 2002}}</ref> In ''Lockdown'' T.O.M. fights to save the Absolution from an attack by a giant trash compactor.<ref>{{cite web|last=King|first=Brad|title=Game Is on for Cartoon Host|url=https://www.wired.com/techbiz/media/news/2001/09/46529|work=Wired.com|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|accessdate=April 1, 2012|date=September 17, 2001}}</ref> ''Trapped in Hyperspace'', the next TIE, ran the week of September 16\u201320, 2002. Sara gets taken offline by a computer virus named Swayzak (whose voice actor is unknown but is speculated to be [[Khary Payton]]), and TOM is trapped in hyperspace. He manages to defeat Swayzak before the Absolution hits Earth.<ref>{{cite web|last=Harris|first=Jeff|title=Toonami Becomes Trapped in Hyperspace|url=http://www.toonzone.net/forums/showthread.php?48019-Trapped-In-Hyperspace-Official-Press-Release|work=ToonZone.net|accessdate=April 1, 2012|date=September 12, 2002}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The game tie-in for this event is lost.\n\nDuring the week of February 24\u201328, 2003, Cartoon Network aired on Toonami \"Giant Robot Week,\" a five-day special based on [[mecha]] series, which were licensed by [[A.D. Vision]].  The series shown were ''[[Neon Genesis Evangelion]]'', ''[[Gigantor]]'', ''[[Robotech]]'', ''[[Martian Successor Nadesico]]'', and ''[[Dai-Guard]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Evangelion, Nadesico, Dai-Guard, Robotech to Air on Cartoon Network|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2003-01-28/evangelion-nadesico-dai-guard-robotech-to-air-on-cartoon-network|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|date=January 28, 2003|accessdate=September 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 2001, Cartoon Network released ''[[Toonami: Deep Space Bass]]'', the official soundtrack album to the TV block.\n\n====2003\u20132007: T.O.M. 3 era====\nIn March 2003, TOM was revamped into a more muscular figure. This was explained in-universe as him being rebuilt after fighting a space pirate. His voice also became more humanlike.\n\nIn September 2003, a mini series premiered introducing a new, [[2D computer graphics|2D]] universe. ''[[Immortal Grand Prix]]'' (''IGPX''), created by Toonami producers Sean Akins and Jason DeMarco, and produced by [[anime]] studio [[Production I.G]], aired in five short installments, serving as a pilot for the second Toonami original series, which premiered in November 2005<ref>{{cite web|last=Bynum|first=Aaron H.|title=CN Upfront: TOONAMI Programming|url=http://www.animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=597|work=AnimationInsider.net|accessdate=April 2, 2012|date=February 16, 2005}}</ref>\n\nOn April 17, 2004, Toonami was moved from weekday afternoons to a Saturday evening slot, where it aired regularly for four hours starting at 7:00&nbsp;pm EST.<ref name=\"miguzi\">{{cite web|title=Cartoon Network Announces New Action-Adventure Programming Strategy|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2004-02-26/cartoon-network-announces-new-action-adventure-programming-strategy|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 2, 2012|date=February 26, 2004}}</ref> A new lighter-toned action block, Miguzi, to weekdays in its place.<ref name=\"miguzi\"/> Toonami also replaced the block known as Saturday Video Entertainment System (SVES).  One reason for the move from weekdays to Saturday nights was because some of the shows on the weekday lineup became too violent for a weekday broadcast on the network. The new Toonami lineup showcased anime such as ''[[Naruto]]'', ''Rave Master'', ''[[Duel Masters]]'', ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam SEED]]'', ''[[One Piece (TV series)|One Piece]]'', ''[[Bobobo-bo Bo-bobo]]'', ''[[Zatch Bell]]'', and ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Chronicles]]'', as well as premiered North American productions including ''[[Teen Titans (TV series)|Teen Titans]]'', ''[[Megas XLR]]'', ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]'', and ''[[IGPX]]'', Toonami's first and only original production co-produced by [[Production I.G]] and [[Bandai Entertainment]]. Sara got a full body during this period, and became more anime-esque, along with her voice actress being changed to British actress and ''Red Dwarf'' star [[Samantha Robson]].\n\nAlthough ''[[Megas XLR]]'' was the first original American-made franchise to actually debut on the block, it was initially a Cartoon Network original that was planned to air on Friday nights.  Other Cartoon Network action properties, namely ''[[Samurai Jack]]'', ''[[Teen Titans (TV series)|Teen Titans]]'', and ''[[Justice League (TV series)|Justice League]]'', aired on Toonami, but were not exclusive to the block until their final seasons.\n\n====2007\u20132008: T.O.M. 4 era and cancellation====\nOn January 27, 2007, a [[teaser trailer|teaser]] commercial aired during the ''[[Xiaolin Showdown]]'' marathon on Cartoon Network, featuring closeup shots of larger Clydes (the remote robot explorers that have been a fixture of Toonami since the beginning) and two new robot A.I's along with the date \"3/17/07\" and T.O.M.'s chest emblem glowing blue. On March 17, Toonami celebrated its 10th anniversary with a new packaging and numerous [[Montage (filmmaking)|montages]] celebrating the block. T.O.M. was revamped into a shorter robot, who was a commander of a jungle control room and aided by two new robots, Flash ([[Dave Wittenberg]]) and D ([[Tom Kenny]]). The montages included a look at past hosts, former logos, and a decade's worth of clips and [[voice-over]]s from shows that aired on Toonami. There were a total of four montages, each with different clips, and three were one minute long.\n\nAs part of the anniversary (and to coincide with Cartoon Network's March Movie Madness event), Toonami planned another month of movies:\n* March 3 \u2013 ''[[The Invincible Iron Man (film)|The Invincible Iron Man]]''\n* March 10 \u2013 ''[[Mosaic (film)|Mosaic]]''\n* March 17 \u2013 ''[[Hellboy: Blood and Iron]]''\n* March 24 \u2013 ''[[Stan Lee Presents: The Condor]]''\n* March 31 \u2013 ''[[Spirited Away]]'' and ''[[Teen Titans: Trouble in Tokyo]]''\n\nOn September 20, 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-09-20/cartoon-network-to-reportedly-end-toonami-tonight|title=Cartoon Network to End Toonami on September 20 (Updated)|date=September 20, 2008|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> at the [[Anime Weekend Atlanta]] convention in Atlanta, Georgia, Cartoon Network announced that they had cancelled the Toonami block due to low ratings. Toonami then aired its final broadcast later that same evening. The final show to air on the block was a rerun of ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' at 10:30 PM. Employees who worked on the block moved to other parts of the channel, except for Dennis Moloney, who left Turner to work for [[Disney]]. Toonami Jetstream remained with the Toonami name until January 30, 2009. At the end of Toonami's final airing, T.O.M. 4 ended the block with a brief, final monologue, backed by the song \"Cascade\" by [[Tycho (musician)|Tycho]]:\n\n{{cquote|Well, [[The End (The Doors song)|this is the end, beautiful friends.]] After more than 11 years, this is Toonami's final broadcast. It's been a lot of fun, and we'd like to thank each and every one of you who made this journey with us. Toonami wouldn't have been anything without you. Hopefully, we've left you with some good memories. So, until we meet again, [[The Outsiders (novel)|stay gold.]] [[Cowboy Bebop|Bang.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/video/index.html?episodeID=8a250ab033ff6e9301343946df930141 |title=Videos &#124; Watch Free Online Videos |publisher=Cartoon Network |date= |accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nAfter Toonami's final episode on TV, Toonami Jetstream's subsequent shut down in 2009 marked the end of this incarnation until the brand's revival in 2012.\n\n===Adult Swim (2012\u2013present)===\n====2012\u20132013====\nOn April 1, 2012, Adult Swim aired the Toonami block for their annual [[April Fools' Day]] prank, in which would be the annual airing of ''[[The Room (2003 film)|The Room]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geekosystem.com/april-fools-2012/|title=April Fools\u2019 2012 Around the Web|last=Eddy|first=Max|date=April 1, 2012|work=Geekosystem.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> After airing that week's scheduled episode of ''[[Bleach (TV series)|Bleach]]'', the Toonami-related programming continued throughout the night, featuring shows such as ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'', ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam Wing]]'', ''[[Tenchi Muyo! Ryo-Ohki|Tenchi Muyo!]]'', ''[[Outlaw Star]]'', ''[[The Big O]]'', ''[[Yu Yu Hakusho]]'', ''[[Blue Submarine No. 6]]'', ''[[Trigun]]'', [[Astro Boy (1963 TV series)|''Astro Boy'' (1963)]], and ''[[Gigantor]]''. The following day, Adult Swim posted a message to their [[Twitter]] page, simply stating, \"Want it back? Let us know. [[Hashtag|#]]BringBackToonami\".<ref>{{cite tweet |author= <nowiki>[adult swim]</nowiki> |user= adultswim|number= 187004036824834049 |date= April 2, 2012 |title= Want it back? Let us know. #BringBackToonami |access-date= April 3, 2012 }}</ref> On April 4, Adult Swim followed up this tweet with one stating, \"#BringBackToonami We've heard you. Thank you for your passion and interest - stay tuned.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |author= <nowiki>[adult swim]</nowiki> |user= adultswim|number= 187653853339074560 |date= April 4, 2012 |title= #BringBackToonami We've heard you. Thank you for your passion and interest - stay tuned. |access-date= April 4, 2012 }}</ref> On April 8, Adult Swim aired two bumpers about the Toonami tweets and answered with \"[we're listening]\" and \"[we're looking into it]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Adult Swim: We're listening|url=http://www.theouthousers.com/index.php/news/entertainment-news/18936-adult-swim-were-listening.html|work=TheOuthouse.com|accessdate=April 9, 2012|date=April 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, Adult Swim posted a message on Facebook announcing that Toonami would return on May 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adultswim.com/shows/toonami/index.html |title=Toonami returns May 26 on Adult Swim |publisher=Adultswim.com |date= |accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> The network issued a press release later that day confirming the block's revival as a Saturday late-night action block.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20120516007065/en|title=Adult Swim Announces Largest Programming Schedule Ever for 2012-13|location=Atlanta, GA|publisher=Adult Swim|agency=Business Wire|via=Business Wire|date=May 16, 2012|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}</ref> Toonami made its return on May 26, with an initial lineup consisting of current Adult Swim Action programs, along with premieres of ''[[Deadman Wonderland]]'' and ''[[Casshern Sins]]''. On August 18, ''[[Samurai 7]]'' and ''[[Eureka Seven]]'' replaced ''Deadman Wonderland'' and ''[[Cowboy Bebop]]''. In essence, the revived block is very similar to the Midnight Run of the original, airing uncut programming as well as having more mature themes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-07-31/samurai-7-anime-debuts-on-toonami-on-august-19 |title=Samurai 7 Anime Debuts on Toonami on August 19 |publisher= AnimeNewsNetwork.com |date=July 31, 2012 |accessdate=July 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn October 6, Toonami expanded to a full six hours; ''[[Sym-Bionic Titan]]'' and ''[[ThunderCats (2011 TV series)|ThunderCats]]'' were added to the block.<ref name=cru_toon>{{cite news|last=Green|first=Scott|title=Toonami Expands to Six Hours|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2012/09/26-1/toonami-expands-to-six-hours|accessdate=September 26, 2012|newspaper=Crunchyroll News|date=September 26, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Tenchi Muyo! GXP]]'' was announced as the next premiere on November 3, as was the return of ''[[Inuyasha]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adult Swim's Toonami Block to Show Tenchi Muyo! GXP|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-11-03/adult-swim-toonami-block-to-show-tenchi-muyo-gxp|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=November 5, 2012|date=November 3, 2012}}</ref> On November 22, Toonami announced they would air uncut episodes of ''[[Naruto]]'', and confirmed that ''[[Bleach (TV series)|Bleach]]'' would enter reruns for eight weeks, beginning on December 1.<ref>{{cite web|title=Naruto to Run Uncut on Adult Swim's Toonami Block|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-11-22/naruto-to-run-uncut-on-adult-swim-toonami-block|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=November 23, 2012|date=November 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn January 6, 2013, Toonami introduced a new blue color scheme, after using a similar scheme to introduce ''Inuyasha'' on November 3 of the previous year. New episodes of ''Bleach'' began on January 26.  On February 16, ''[[Soul Eater (manga)|Soul Eater]]'' began airing on Toonami, replacing ''Samurai 7''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toonami.tumblr.com/post/42169576098/tv-guide-youre-an-asshole|title=TV GUIDE, YOU\u2019RE AN ASSHOLE.|date=February 3, 2013}}</ref> During [[MomoCon]], new designs for both T.O.M and the Absolution were unveiled, along with the announcement that overall design of the block would be changed.<ref name=\"toonami.tumblr.com\">{{cite web|url=http://toonami.tumblr.com/post/46385114366/april-27th-why-should-you-care-about-april-27th|title=Toonami|work=tumblr.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u20132019====\nOn April 27, 2013 Toonami premiered its new look, featuring the return of supporting host Sara (now voiced by Adult Swim staff member [[Dana Swanson]].) To kick off 2014, Toonami premiered the anime ''[[Space Dandy]]'' on January 4, even before Japan. The anime ran for two seasons and 26 episodes before ending that September. The block introduced a new aesthetic on April 6. This new look also featured the return of the ''[[Ninja Tune]]'' record label to Toonami.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toonami.tumblr.com/post/81694903800/lots-of-little-goodies-coming-tomorrow|title=Toonami|work=tumblr.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> ''Intruder II'', the first Total Immersion Event since Toonami's 2012 revival, began on November 7 and concluded on December 20, 2015 with Sonny Strait reprising his role as Invader with Steve Blum, who also is the invader and TOM 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toonami.tumblr.com/post/132775382573/its-been-a-long-time-coming-intruder-ii-begins|title=Toonami|publisher=}}</ref> On December 2, Adult Swim announced that a new season of ''[[Sword Art Online]]'' in July 27, 2013 and  ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' was being produced. It ended up premiering on Toonami in March 2017.<ref name=SamJack2016>{{cite web|title=Toonami|url=http://toonami.tumblr.com/post/134405148218/adult-swim-is-excited-to-announce-that-jack-is|website=tumblr.com|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/03/11/519807686/-samurai-jack-cartoon-to-air-final-season-12-years-later|title='Samurai Jack' Cartoon To Air Final Season, 12 Years Later|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|website=[[NPR.org]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/samurai-jack-return-cartoon-network-next-year-229189|title=Samurai Jack to return next year on Adult Swim|website=[[The A.V. Club]]}}</ref> The conclusion of ''Intruder III'' in 2016 led to another new look to Toonami.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-07-02/toonami-runs-mamoru-oshii-production-i.g-micro-series-in-2017/.103880|title=Toonami Runs Mamoru Oshii, Production I.G's Micro-Series in 2017|work=Anime News Network|date=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 31, 2016, Toonami aired its first subtitled anime broadcast with the music video of [[Porter Robinson]] and [[Madeon]]'s ''[[Shelter (Porter Robinson and Madeon song)|Shelter]]'', produced in collaboration with [[A-1 Pictures]] and [[Crunchyroll]]. However, the subtitled parts in both the start and end of the music video have been removed due to an unknown error. As of right now, it is unknown that the full version of the music video could air in the future.\n\nOn March 20, 2018, Production I.G. and Adult Swim announced that two new seasons of [[FLCL]], ''FLCL Progressive'', and ''FLCL Alternative'' would premiere on Toonami in 2018, with the date set for June 2 at 11:30PM.<ref name=\"2016 reveal\">{{cite web|title=Toonami to Co-Produce 2 New FLCL Seasons|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-03-24/toonami-to-co-produce-2-new-flcl-seasons/.100222|website=Anime News Network|accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Toho involvement\">{{cite web|title=ANIME EXPO 2017: FLCL 2 AND 3 FIRST DETAILS, RELEASE WINDOW ANNOUNCED|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2017/07/02/anime-expo-2017-flcl-2-and-3-first-details-release-window-announced|website=IGN|accessdate=March 20, 2018|date=July 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/flcl-season-2-3-adult-swim-853752|title=New \u2018FLCL\u2019 Seasons Premiere on Adult Swim this June|publisher=newsweek|access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/updated-adult-swim-announces-two-new-seasons-of-cult-a-1798245721|title=Adult Swim announces two new seasons of cult anime hit FLCL|website=[[The A.V. Club]]}}</ref> On [[April Fools' Day]] 2018, Toonami was entirely dubbed in Japanese and kicked the prank off by airing a preview of the first episode of ''FLCL Alternative'' in Japanese with English subtitles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/4/2/17180894/flcl-3-alternative-toonami-adult-swim-april-fools|title=FLCL season 3 premieres as Adult Swim\u2019s April Fools\u2019 prank|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> The Toonami logo was also changed to Japanese (stylized as \u30c8\u30a6\u30ca\u30df). Toonami followed the sneak preview by airing the film ''[[Mind Game (film)|Mind Game]]'' and aired programming after that was originally scheduled after ''Black Clover'', except ''Iron-Blooded Orphans'', in original Japanese with English subtitles. TOM was voiced by Masa Kanome, a Japanese stunt actor who had been in a Wolverine movie, and Sara was voiced by Fusako Shiotani.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/adult-swim-celebrates-this-years-april-fools-by-running-1824238556|title=Adult Swim celebrates this year's April Fools by running a new FLCL episode months ahead of schedule|website=[[The A.V. Club]]}}</ref>\n\nOn September 29, Toonami expanded to seven full hours from 9 PM to 4 AM with ''[[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]'' as the marquee addition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/2018/09/12/toonami-schedule-anime-expand-boruto-dragon-ball/|title=Toonami Expands Program With New Schedule, Shows|work=Comicbook|accessdate=September 12, 2018}}</ref> On December 13, it was announced that Toonami would remove ''Dragon Ball Z Kai'' and ''Samurai Jack'' from its lineup, cutting the block down to 6 hours. Also, the block would be moved back and would air from 11PM-5AM, starting on January 5, 2019, because of Adult Swim taking back the 8pm hour from Cartoon Network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Toonami/photos/a.1442483259375850/2053278171629686/?type=3|title=Toonami's new year schedule|website=Facebook|accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 24, it was announced that Toonami would remove ''Pop Team Epic'' and ''Iron-Blooded Orphans'' from its lineup, cutting the block down to 5 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Toonami/photos/a.1442483259375850/2077741649183338/?type=3&theater|title=Toonami\u2019s going back to our sweet spot!|website=facebook|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2019, Adult Swim announced that Toonami will be shifting its whole block thirty minutes earlier, starting at 10:30PM and ending at 3:30 AM, cutting a half hour rerun of ''[[Family Guy]]''. The changes will begin on May 25, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/anime/2019/05/13/toonami-schedule-change-may-25-attack-on-titan-season-3-part-2/|title=Toonami Announces Major May Schedule Shift|website=comicbook|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 24, 2019, MomoCon announced that a new T.I.E., ''The Forge'', will begin airing on November 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ToonamiNews/status/1132079941007355904|title=Toonami's \"The Forge\" Coming November 9th|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=May 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn June 27, 2019, it was announced that Toonami will be shifting its whole block back at 11:00PM and ending at 4:00 AM, in addition to premiering ''[[Food Wars!: Shokugeki no Soma]]'' at 1:00AM. The changes will begin on July 6, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Toonami/photos/a.1442483259375850/2175293802761455/?type=3|title=Toonami Reveals Surprising July Schedule Shift|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> On July 4th at Anime Expo and on Facebook, it was announced that ''[[Demon Slayer: Kimetsu no Yaiba]]'' would be joining the block this Fall.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/1440408039583372/posts/2179755838981918?sfns=mo</ref> On July 7 at RTX 2019, it was announced that ''[[Gen:Lock]]'' would be joining the block on August 3.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/genlock-sets-adult-swim-premiere-date-1203260586/|title=Animated Series \u2018gen:LOCK\u2019 Sets Adult Swim Premiere Date|magazine=Variety|accessdate=July 7, 2019}}</ref> On August 16, it was announced that Toonami will expand 30 minutes and reshuffling its block with ''[[Dr. Stone]]'' at 12:00 AM.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/1440408039583372/posts/2208431249447710?sfns=mo|title=Dr. Stone coming to Toonami|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=August 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2020\u2013present====\nOn January 8, 2020, it was announced that ''[[Sword Art Online: Alicization|Sword Art Online: Alicization \u2013 War of Underworld]]'' would premiere on the network on January 18.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2020/01/08-1/sword-art-online-alicization-war-of-the-underworld-hits-toonami-on-january-18 |title=Sword Art Online Alicization War Of The Underworld Hits Toonami On January 18 |last=Luster |first=Joesph |date=January 8, 2020 |website=Crunchyroll}}</ref> On January 23, it was announced that Toonami would be reducing the block to five hours, as ''Fire Force'' was ending its run; the new block aired from 11:00 PM to 4:00 AM.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bubbleblabber.com/adult-swim-schedule-updates-new-toonami-schedule-for-february-ballmastrz-9009-season-two-gets-start-date-and-time/|title=Adult Swim Schedule Updates: New Toonami Schedule For February ; Ballmastrz: 9009 Season Two Gets Start Date And Time|publisher=bubbleblabber|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> On February 6, it was announced that the block would lose another one and a half hours, as ''Dr. Stone'' was ending its run, while reruns of ''The Promised Neverland'' and ''Attack on Titan'' would also cease. This reduced the length of the block to three and a half hours, which aired from 11:30 PM to 3:00 AM.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ToonamiNews/status/1225485729557549066|title=Toonami Delays New My Hero Academia Episode in Schedule Shift|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> On April 8, it was announced that Toonami would be reduced to a three-hour block, as ''Sword Art Online: Alicization - War of Underworld'' was ending its run.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/anime/2020/04/08/toonami-new-schedule-anime-april-2020-shorter/|title=Toonami Announces New Schedule with Shortened Airtime|publisher=comicbook|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> On April 15, it was announced that ''[[Paranoia Agent]]''  would premiere on April 25 and that ''Food Wars: Shokugeki no Soma'' would be removed from the block until a new agreement was struck for the next three seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2020/04/15/cartoon-networks-toonami-adds-satoshi-kons-paranoia-agent-tv-anime-in-latest-schedule-update|title=Cartoon Network's Toonami Adds Satoshi Kon's Paranoia Agent TV Anime In Latest Schedule Update|publisher=Crunchyroll|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Online video services==\n===Toonami Reactor===\nOn March 26, 2001, Cartoon Network launched Toonami Reactor, their first online streaming video service.<ref>{{cite web|title=Large Toonami Updates|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2001-03-27/large-toonami-updates|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012|date=March 27, 2001}}</ref> The three-month service featured streaming episodes from ''Dragon Ball Z'' and ''[[Space Battleship Yamato|Star Blazers]]'', the latter of which was an online-exclusive series. Editorial content was provided by the now-defunct ''[[Animerica|Animerica Magazine]]'', published by [[VIZ Media]]. After the three-month \"trial run\" was over, Cartoon Network took it offline and completely revamped it.\n\nOn November 14, 2001, Cartoon Network relaunched Toonami Reactor with all online-exclusive programs such as ''[[Star Blazers]]'', ''[[Patlabor: The TV Series]]'', ''[[Captain Harlock|Harlock Saga]]'', and ''[[Record of Lodoss War]]'', as well as videos from Daft Punk and Toonami-themed games.  In the summer of 2002, Toonami Reactor was revamped again under the Adult Swim aegis and, in a joint venture with VIZ's ''[[Weekly Shonen Jump]]'', programmed it as \"Adult Swim Pipeline.\" It featured episodes and/or manga chapters from ''[[One Piece]]'', ''[[Naruto]]'', ''[[Shaman King]]'', ''[[Yu Yu Hakusho]]'', and ''[[Sand Land]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adultswim.com/pipeline/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030411064900/http://www.adultswim.com/pipeline/index.html|title=Adult Swim - Pipeline|archivedate=April 11, 2003|work=adultswim.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://adultswim.com/pipeline/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030207193313/http://adultswim.com/pipeline/index.html|title=Adult Swim|archivedate=February 7, 2003|work=adultswim.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Toonami Jetstream===\n{{main|Toonami Jetstream}}\nOn April 25, 2006, Cartoon Network and VIZ Media announced plans<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/pressrelease.php?id=1685|title=Cartoon Network and VIZ Media Announce Broadband Joint Venture, Toonami Jetstream|date=April 25, 2006|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> to launch [[Toonami Jetstream]], a new ad-supported streaming video service featuring Toonami series like ''Naruto'', ''Samurai Jack'', ''Megas XLR'', and ''IGPX'', and the Internet [[webcast]] premieres of ''[[Hikaru no Go]]'', ''[[M\u00c4R]]'', ''[[Eyeshield 21]]'', ''[[The Prince of Tennis]], [[MegaMan Star Force]]'', ''[[Kiba (anime)|Kiba]]'', ''[[MegaMan NT Warrior]]'', and ''[[Zoids: Genesis]]'', the latter two of which were never streamed.\n\nToonami Jetstream launched on July 17, 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogcritics.org/scitech/article/cartoon-networks-toonami-jetstream-to-begin/|title=Cartoon Network's Toonami Jetstream to Begin Streaming Video|author=TeevBlogger|date=April 28, 2006|work=Blogcritics.org|publisher=Technorati|accessdate=April 1, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017184326/http://blogcritics.org/scitech/article/cartoon-networks-toonami-jetstream-to-begin/|archivedate=October 17, 2011}}</ref> (after a brief unofficial sneak preview that began on July 14), and offered episodes of ''Naruto'', ''Hikaru no Go'', ''M\u00c4R'', ''[[Zatch Bell!]]'', ''Pok\u00e9mon'', ''[[Blue Dragon (video game)|Blue Dragon]]'', ''Samurai Jack'', ''Kiba'', ''[[Storm Hawks]]'' and ''[[Transformers: Animated]]''.\n\nOn January 31, 2009, Toonami Jetstream was discontinued.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-01-31/toonami-jetstream-video-streaming-service-shuts-down|title=Toonami Jetstream Video-Streaming Service Shuts Down|date=January 31, 2009|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> Since then, many of the shows aired until cancellation aired on Cartoon Network Video on its main website.\n\nIn 2012, Adult Swim rebranded their action videos section as \"Toonami shows.\" It initially featured content from ''[[Durarara!!]]'', which never aired on the block.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adultswim.com/shows/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816034804/http://www.adultswim.com/shows/index.html|title=Watch TV Show Episodes and Clips for Free from Adult Swim|archivedate=August 16, 2012|work=adultswim.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Toonami Pre-Flight===\nOn February 27, 2015, adultswim.com launched the online show ''Toonami: Pre-Flight'' hosted by Toonami producers Jason DeMarco and Gill Austin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adultswim.com/preflight|title=Adult Swim Streams - Live Stream|publisher=|accessdate=December 30, 2016}}</ref><!-- As of toonami.com/preflight --> The first two episodes premiered on a Friday at 5:00&nbsp;p.m. Eastern time, and was then moved to Tuesday at 5:00&nbsp;p.m. Eastern time until September 25, 2015, when the show was moved back to Fridays at 6:30&nbsp;p.m. Eastern time. Each episode features a series highlight, a weekly topic and other featurettes like sneak peeks at promos and spots, as well as announcements, and segments from voiceover talent [[Steve Blum]] and Dana Swanson. Toonami has also done panels from [[MomoCon]], [[San Diego Comic-Con International|San Diego Comic-Con]], [[Dragon Con]] and [[Anime Expo]] which they've streamed as part of Pre-Flight either live or on tape delay.\n\n=== Crunchyroll ===\nThe anime-oriented streaming service [[Crunchyroll]] became a sibling asset to Adult Swim after [[AT&T]]'s acquisition of [[Time Warner]], and its subsequent acquisition of the remaining shares in AT&T's existing venture [[Otter Media]]. In March 2019, after both Adult Swim and Otter were placed under Warner Bros. as part of a corporate reorganization, it was announced that there would be synergies between Toonami and the service. The two properties had already announced a collaboration on [[Blade Runner (franchise)#Blade Runner: Black Lotus (2019)|''Blade Runner: Black Lotus'']], an anime series set within the ''[[Blade Runner]]'' universe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/otter-media-acquired-att-crunchyroll-fullscreen-rooster-teeth-1202441941/|title=AT&T Acquires Rest Of Otter Media To Fold Into New WarnerMedia|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Patrick Hipes|date=August 7, 2018|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/3/12/18261643/adult-swim-crunchyroll-anime-series|title=Adult Swim and Crunchyroll are hooking up to bring more anime to TV|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=2019-03-12|website=Polygon|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Programming==\n{{main|List of programs broadcast by Toonami}}\n\n===Cartoon Network (1997\u20132008) / Kids' WB (2001\u20132002)===\n;1997\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[ThunderCats (1985 TV series)|ThunderCats]]'' <small>(1985 series)</small>\n* ''Cartoon Roulette'' <small>(composed of ''[[Space Ghost (TV series)]]'', ''[[Birdman and the Galaxy Trio]]'', ''[[The Herculoids]]'', ''[[Mightor]]'', ''[[Shazzan]]'', ''[[Teen Force]]'', ''[[The Impossibles (TV series)|The Impossibles]]'', and the 1940s ''[[Superman (1940s cartoons)|Superman]]'' cartoons)</small>\n* ''[[Voltron (1984 TV series)|Voltron]]''\n* ''[[The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest]]''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n;1998\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Robotech (TV series)|Robotech]]''\n* ''[[Beast Wars: Transformers]]''\n* ''[[Sailor Moon (TV series)|Sailor Moon]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball Z]] ''\n* ''[[Super Friends]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;1999\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[ReBoot]]''\n* ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]''\n* ''[[Ronin Warriors]]''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2000\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[G-Force: Guardians of Space]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam Wing]]''\n* ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]''\n* ''[[Tenchi Muyo! Ryo-Ohki]]''\n* ''[[Tenchi Universe]]''\n* ''[[Tenchi in Tokyo]]''\n* ''[[Blue Submarine No. 6]]''\n* ''[[Superman: The Animated Series]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2001\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Outlaw Star]]''\n* ''[[The Big O]]''\n* ''[[Cardcaptors]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam: The 08th MS Team]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball (anime)|Dragon Ball]]''\n* ''[[Batman Beyond]]''\n* ''[[Zoids: New Century]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam 0080: War in the Pocket]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2002\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Hamtaro]]''\n* ''[[Zoids: Chaotic Century]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Fighter G Gundam]]''\n* ''[[He-Man and the Masters of the Universe (2002 TV series)|He-Man and the Masters of the Universe]]''\n* ''[[Transformers: Armada]]''\n* ''[[G.I. Joe: A Real American Hero (1985 TV series)|G.I. Joe]]''\n* ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' <small>(original series)</small>\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2003\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[.hack//Sign]]''\n* ''[[Yu Yu Hakusho]]''\n* ''[[Rurouni Kenshin]]''\n* ''[[Justice League (TV series)|Justice League]]''\n* ''[[Cyborg 009|Cyborg 009: The Cyborg Soldier]]''\n* ''[[Superior Defender Gundam Force]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball GT]]''\n* ''[[Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|Star Wars: Clone Wars]]''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2004\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Duel Masters]]''\n* ''[[Astro Boy (2003 TV series)|Astro Boy]]''\n* ''[[Transformers: Energon]]''\n* ''[[Jackie Chan Adventures]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam SEED]]''\n* ''[[Megas XLR]]''\n* ''[[Rave Master]]''\n* ''[[Teen Titans (TV series)|Teen Titans]]''\n* ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2005\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[D.I.C.E.]]''\n* ''[[Zatch Bell!]]''\n* ''[[The Batman (TV series)|The Batman]]''\n* ''[[One Piece (TV series)|One Piece]]''\n* ''[[Transformers: Cybertron]]''\n* ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Monsters|Yu-Gi-Oh!]]''\n* ''[[Naruto]]''\n* ''[[Bobobo-bo Bo-bobo]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'' <small>(uncut)</small>\n* ''[[Immortal Grand Prix|IGPX]]'' <small>(television series)</small>\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2006\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Wulin Warriors]]''\n* ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Chronicles]]''\n* ''[[Fantastic Four: World's Greatest Heroes]]''\n* ''[[Pok\u00e9mon: Battle Frontier]]''\n* ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! GX]]''\n* ''[[M\u00c4R]]''\n* ''[[The Prince of Tennis]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2007\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Mega Man Star Force (anime)|Mega Man Star Force]]''\n* ''[[Storm Hawks]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2008\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Bakugan Battle Brawlers]]''\n* ''[[Blue Dragon (anime)|Blue Dragon]]''\n* ''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Adult Swim (2012\u2013present)===\n;2012\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Bleach (TV series)|Bleach]]''\n* ''[[Deadman Wonderland]]''\n* ''[[Casshern Sins]]''\n* ''[[Fullmetal Alchemist: Brotherhood]]''\n* ''[[Ghost in the Shell: S.A.C 2nd GIG]]''\n* ''[[Cowboy Bebop]]''\n* ''[[Ghost in the Shell: Stand Alone Complex]]''\n* ''[[Samurai 7]]''\n* ''[[Eureka Seven]]''\n* ''[[Sym-Bionic Titan]]''\n* ''[[ThunderCats (2011 TV series)|ThunderCats]]'' <small>(2011 series)</small>\n* ''[[Inuyasha]]''\n* ''[[Tenchi Muyo! GXP]]''\n* ''[[Naruto]]'' <small>(uncut)</small>\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2013\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Soul Eater (manga)|Soul Eater]]''\n* ''[[Immortal Grand Prix|IGPX]]'' <small>(television series)</small>\n* ''[[One Piece (TV series)|One Piece]]'' <small>(uncut)</small>\n* ''[[Sword Art Online]]''\n* ''[[The Big O|The Big O II]]''\n* ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]''\n* ''[[FLCL]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2014\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Space Dandy]]''\n* ''[[Naruto#Naruto: Shippuden|Naruto: Shippuden]]'' <small>(uncut)</small>\n* ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' <small>(original series / Seasons 1\u20134)</small>\n* ''[[Blue Exorcist]]''\n* ''[[Black Lagoon]]''\n* ''[[Attack on Titan]]''\n* ''[[Black Lagoon|Black Lagoon: The Second Barrage]]''\n* ''[[Beware the Batman]]''\n* ''[[Gurren Lagann]]''\n* ''[[Hellsing Ultimate]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball Z#Dragon Ball Z Kai|Dragon Ball Z Kai]]'' <small>(uncut)</small>\n* ''[[Inuyasha: The Final Act]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2015\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Kill la Kill]]''\n* ''[[Sword Art Online II]]''\n* ''[[Michiko & Hatchin]]''\n* ''[[Akame ga Kill!]]''\n* ''[[Parasyte|Parasyte -the maxim-]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2016\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Samurai Champloo]]''\n* ''[[Dimension W]]''\n* ''[[Hunter \u00d7 Hunter]]'' <small>(2011 series)</small>\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam: Iron-Blooded Orphans]]''\n* ''[[One-Punch Man]]''\n* ''[[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure (2012 TV series)|JoJo's Bizarre Adventure: The Animation]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2017\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Dragon Ball Super]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball Z#Dragon Ball Z Kai|Dragon Ball Z Kai: The Final Chapters]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam Unicorn|Mobile Suit Gundam Unicorn RE:0096]]''\n* ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' <small>(revival series / Season 5)</small>\n* ''[[Tokyo Ghoul]]''\n* ''[[Lupin the 3rd Part IV: The Italian Adventure]]''\n* ''[[Tokyo Ghoul \u221aA]]''\n* ''[[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure: Stardust Crusaders]]''\n* ''[[Outlaw Star]]'' <small>(HD)</small>\n* ''[[Black Clover]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2018\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[My Hero Academia]]''\n* ''[[FLCL|FLCL Progressive]]''\n* ''[[Pop Team Epic]]''\n* ''[[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure: Diamond Is Unbreakable]]''\n* ''[[FLCL|FLCL Alternative]]''\n* ''[[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]''\n* ''[[Mob Psycho 100]]''\n* ''[[Megalo Box]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2019\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Sword Art Online: Alicization]]''\n* ''[[The Promised Neverland]]''\n* ''[[Lupin the Third Part 5]]''\n* ''[[Food Wars!: Shokugeki no Soma]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam: The Origin|Mobile Suit Gundam: The Origin - Advent of the Red Comet]]''\n* ''[[Fire Force]]''\n* ''[[Gen:Lock]]''\n* ''[[Dr. Stone]]''\n* ''[[Demon Slayer: Kimetsu no Yaiba]]''\n* ''[[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure: Golden Wind]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2020\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Sword Art Online: Alicization|Sword Art Online: Alicization \u2013 War of Underworld]]''\n* ''[[Paranoia Agent]]''\n* ''[[Uzumaki]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==International==\nOutside the United States, Cartoon Network aired Toonami blocks in Australia from 2001 to 2006. In the United Kingdom, Toonami was a standalone channel from 2003 to 2007. In December 2012, Toonami was launched as a standalone channel in Asia-Pacific. Similar channels were launched in India in 2015, France in 2016 and Africa in 2017. The Southeast Asian and Indian channels have since been closed.\n\n===Australia===\n{{Main|Toonami (Australian TV programming block)}}\nThe programming block was launched in 2001 in Australia as a weekend block on [[Cartoon Network (Australia and New Zealand)|Cartoon Network]]. It aired on Saturday from 6:00 pm to 8:00 pm and on Sunday from 3:00 pm to 5:00 pm with a repeat on both nights from 11:00 pm to 1:00 am. The programming was then converted to a weekday block shortly there after. The programming was dropped from the channel in August 2006.\n\n===France===\n{{Main|Toonami (France)}}\nFrench version of the Toonami television channel was launched on February 11, 2016. It is operated by [[Turner Broadcasting System Europe]].\n\n===India===\n{{Main|Toonami (India)}}\nAn Indian version of Toonami was first launched as a block in 2001 and was then followed by a stand-alone channel in 2015. It ceased operations in May 15, 2018.\n\n===Latin America===\n{{Main|Toonami (Latin America)}}\nOn December 2, 2002, Cartoon Network premiered Toonami block, replacing a similarly-themed block, Talisman. The weekend block of Toonami was then replaced by the premiere of Adult Swim in Latin America on October 7, 2005. In 2007, Cartoon Network cut the Toonami block completely from the channel.\n\n===Pakistan===\nToonami was launched as a programming block in Pakistan on [[Cartoon Network (Pakistan)|Cartoon Network]] and ran from 2004\u20132013.\n\n===Southeast Asia===\n{{Main|Toonami (Southeast Asia)}}\nA stand-alone Toonami channel was launched in Southeast Asia replacing [[Boomerang (Southeast Asian TV channel)|Boomerang]] on December 1, 2012. Although it replaced Boomerang, the channel was relaunched in 2015 alongside Toonami. The channel shut down on March 31, 2018 making it the longest running stand alone channel out all of them lasting 6 years.\n\n===Sub-Saharan Africa===\nA Toonami television channel was launched in sub-Saharan Africa on June 1, 2017. It is available on Kwes\u00e9 satellite television platform.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/turners-toonami-finds-africa-pay-tv-home/?doing_wp_cron=1496335314.8652520179748535156250 |title=Turner\u2019s Toonami Finds Africa Pay TV Home |date=2017-05-31 |website=Animation Magazine |language=en-US |access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\n===UK & Ireland===\n{{Main|Toonami (UK & Ireland)}}\nToonami was launched as a programming block on [[Cartoon Network (UK & Ireland)|Cartoon Network]] in the UK and Ireland in 2001. In October 2002, it then became part of [[CNX (TV channel)|CNX]], a new spin-off channel. Almost a year later, CNX was relaunched as Toonami in 2003 turning the block into a stand-alone channel. The channel shut down on May 24, 2007.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Television|United States|Anime and manga|Cartoon|Cartoon Network|1990s}}\n<!-- ({{NoMoreLinks}}) -->\n<!-- DO NOT ADD MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS ----- If you think that your link might be useful, instead of placing it here, put it on this article's discussion page first. Links that have not been verified WILL BE DELETED -->\n* {{Official website|https://www.adultswim.com/toonami/}}\n<!--\nDo not add Facebook and Twitter et al. There are MANY and all are linked from the campaign site.\n-->\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Toonami-anime}}\n{{Warner Bros.}}\n{{Cartoon Network}}\n{{Adult Swim original programming}}\n{{Williams Street}}\n{{Kids' WB}}\n{{KidsTVBlocksUS}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Toonami]]\n[[Category:Adult Swim]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network programming blocks]]\n[[Category:Williams Street]]\n[[Category:Television programming blocks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anime television]]\n[[Category:1997 introductions]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Zoonami|Tsunami|}}\n{{Short description|TV programming block, mostly animation}}\n{{Infobox programming block\n| name      = Toonami<!-- The current incarnation that began in 2012 -->\n| image     = [[File:Toonami logo 2019.png|250px]]<!-- WARNING: Please follow Wikipedia's logos of pictures. any deleted pictures will be reverted! -->\n| premiered = {{Start date and age|2012|5|26}}\n| closed    =\n| channel   = [[Adult Swim]]\n| country   = United States\n| headquarters = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| format    = [[Anime]] and [[Action film|action]] [[animation]]\n| runtime   = 3 hours\n| voices    = {{plainlist|\n* [[Sonny Strait]] <small>(1999\u20132000, 2015)</small>\n* [[Steven Blum]] <small>(2000\u20132008, 2012\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Dana Swanson]] <small>(2013\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Beau Billingslea]] <small>(2019)</small>}}\n| website   = [https://www.adultswim.com/toonami/ Toonami.com]\n}}\n\n'''Toonami''' ({{IPAc-en|t|u\u02d0|\u02c8|n|\u0251\u02d0|m|i}} {{respell|too|NAH|mee}}) is an American television [[Block programming|programming block]] that primarily broadcasts [[Japan]]ese [[anime]] and [[United States|American]] [[Action film|action]] [[animation]]. It was created by Sean Akins and Jason DeMarco and produced by [[Williams Street]], a division of [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Entertainment]]. The name is a [[portmanteau]] of the words \"[[cartoon]]\" and \"[[tsunami]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.tvguide.com/news/tsunami-wake-episodes-36301/|title = Tsunami's Wake Pulls Episodes|work = [[TV Guide]]|last1 = Fretts|first1 = Bruce|date = 2005-01-19|accessdate = 2018-05-17}}</ref> It currently broadcasts every Saturday night from 12 a.m. to 3 a.m. [[Eastern Time Zone|ET]]/[[Pacific Time Zone|PT]].\n\nToonami initially ran as an afternoon and evening block on [[Cartoon Network]] and was primarily aimed at boys aged 9\u201314. In its original run from 1997 to 2008, the block was known for showcasing action genre anime that became widely popular with American audiences. Toonami is recognized for its distinctive space-themed backdrop, [[anime music video]]s, [[drum and bass]]-flavored soundtrack, and robot host T.O.M. (short for Toonami Operations Module).\n\nOn May 26, 2012, Toonami was relaunched as a block on [[Adult Swim]]. The current incarnation is a rebrand of Adult Swim's Saturday night action block (itself inherited from Toonami's ''Midnight Run'' block), which primarily airs mature Japanese animation.\n\n\n==Broadcast History==\n{{OriginalResearch|section}}\n===Daytime block on Cartoon Network (1997\u20132008)===\n{{Infobox programming block\n| name      = Toonami<br />(Cartoon Network)\n| premiered = {{Start date and age|1997|03|17}}\n| closed    = {{End date and age|2008|9|20}}\n| owner     = [[WarnerMedia|Time Warner]] (through [[Turner Broadcasting System]])\n| channel   = [[Cartoon Network]] <small>(1997\u20132008)</small><br />[[Kids' WB]] <small>(2001\u20132002)</small>\n| country   = United States\n| headquarters = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]\n| format    = [[Anime]] and [[Action film|action]] [[animation]]\n| voices    = {{plainlist|\n* [[C. Martin Croker]] <small>(1997\u20131999)</small>\n* [[Sonny Strait]] <small>(1999\u20132000)</small>\n* [[Steven Blum]] <small>(2000\u20132008)</small>\n* [[Sally Timms]] <small> (2000\u20132007)</small>\n* [[Khary Payton]] <small>(2002)</small>\n* [[Samantha Robson]] <small> (2004\u20132007) </small>\n* [[Dave Wittenberg]] <small>(2007\u20132008)</small>\n* [[Tom Kenny]] <small>(2007\u20132008)</small>}}\n| website   = {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/toonami |date=* |title=Archived official website}}\n}}\n\n====1997\u20131999: Moltar era====\nToonami was [[Cartoon Network]]'s primary action-animation block. The block premiered on March 17, 1997. It initially replaced Power Zone, Cartoon Network's most recent incarnation of the Super Adventures block, which had been a staple on the network since its debut on October 1, 1992. Toonami was originally a weekday afternoon cartoon and action block hosted by ''[[Space Ghost (TV series)|Space Ghost]]'' villain-turned-producer [[Moltar]] (voiced by [[C. Martin Croker]]) at the Ghost Planet Industries building from 1997 to July 9, 1999.\n\n====1999\u20132000: T.O.M. 1 era====\nOn Saturday, July 10, 1999, Cartoon Network relaunched Toonami with a new environment, the Ghost Planet Spaceship ''Absolution'', and a new host named T.O.M. (voiced by [[Sonny Strait]]), which introduced viewers to him with this speech:\n{{cquote|So it's a brand new Toonami, but the mission objectives remain the same. My name is TOM. I'm the new Moltar. Welcome aboard the Ghost Planet Spaceship Absolution, Cartoon Network's first and only interstellar broadcast and exploration vehicle. I'll give you the tour later. From this day forward she is completely responsible for all Toonami transmissions. I'm taking you guys into the new millennium! No big changes now, same show, same attitude; new place to do it, new guy to do it with. I'm not going to waste any more time, let's get back into it. Later.}}\n\nAlso introduced that day was the Midnight Run, a late night block. It was originally a five-hour Saturday night block (technically Sunday) at midnight EST until March 2000, when it moved to weeknights in an hour-long format until January 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/19991117093658/http://cartoonnetwork.com/favorites/toonami/index.html|title=Data Screen|accessdate=November 2, 2016|publisher=cartoonnetwork.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021201080928/http://www.cartoonnetwork.com:80/toonami/watch/tv_shows/ggundam/index.html|title=Tune in: Weekday Afternoons 5.0-7.0 P.M. (E/P)|date=December 1, 2002|accessdate=March 21, 2018|publisher=cartoonnetwork.com}}</ref> It consisted of anime such as ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'', ''[[Sailor Moon]]'', ''[[Voltron (1984 TV series)|Voltron]]'', ''[[Robotech (TV series)|Robotech]]'', ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam Wing]]'', and ''[[Outlaw Star]]''. Midnight Run tended to have more blood and violence than its daytime counterpart, even running an uncut version of ''Gundam Wing'' between March and November 2000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Pope|first=Kyle|title=* Edit List Special - Cartoon Network Interview|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/edit-list/2002-03-04/cartoon-network-interview|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 2, 2012|date=March 4, 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010306023529/http://www.animenewsservice.com/archives/feb22.htm|title=Gundam Wing Uncut To Air On Weeknights|date=March 6, 2000|accessdate=December 14, 2014|publisher=animenewsservice.com}}</ref> One special edition that started on Friday, August 31, 2001, featured music videos such as \u201c[[Clint Eastwood (song)|Clint Eastwood]]\u201d by [[Gorillaz]], and songs by [[Daft Punk]] from their 2001 album [[Discovery (Daft Punk album)|Discovery]], the music videos of which constitute the 2003 Japanese-French musical [[Interstella 5555]], and Kenna's \"Hellbent\u201d.<ref>{{cite web|title=Daft Punk Music Videos on Toonami.com|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2001-08-16/daft-punk-music-videos-on-toonami.com|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 2, 2012|date=August 16, 2001}}</ref> Another event was ''Dragon Ball Z'' taking over the Midnight Run for a week starting on March 26\u201330, 2001.\n\nStarting in September 2000, Toonami presented special interactive events known as Total Immersion Events (TIEs). These TIEs took place both on-air during Toonami and online at the official site, Toonami.com, and always occurred the week that the block's most popular series, ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Toonami Ratings Continue to Rise|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2001-03-21/toonami-ratings-continue-to-rise|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012|date=March 31, 2001}}</ref> returned for a new season. The first TIE was ''The Intruder'', which introduced T.O.M.'s companion, an [[Artificial intelligence|AI]] matrix known as Sara (voiced by country singer \"Cowboy\" [[Sally Timms]].) ''The Intruder'' was an eight episode mini-series that aired during Toonami from September 18\u201322, 2000. It involved the Absolution being attacked by an alien blob known only as \"the Intruder\", which ultimately devoured T.O.M.\n\n====2000\u20132003: T.O.M. 2 era====\n[[File:Toonami logo.svg|thumb|250px|Toonami logo used from February 21, 2000 to March 14, 2003; revived in 2017 for its 20th anniversary]]\nThough ''The Intruder'' resulted in the destruction of T.O.M., he was soon after upgraded by S.A.R.A. from a short [[Bomberman]]-esque character to a taller, sleeker, deeper-voiced incarnation dubbed T.O.M. 2 (voiced by [[Steven Blum]], who has since been the voice of all subsequent incarnations of the character).\n\nA Saturday morning incarnation, Toonami Rising Sun, ran from 2000 to 2001 at 9:00&nbsp;am to noon. It later ran from 10:00&nbsp;am to 1:00&nbsp;pm, then 11:00&nbsp;am to 1:00&nbsp;pm. This block was somewhat hampered to avoid competing with sister network Kids' WB.\n\nFrom July 30, 2001, until June 28, 2002, [[Kids' WB]] (also owned by [[WarnerMedia|Time Warner]]) aired a Toonami block that was, more or less, the Kids' WB lineup with the Toonami name. It was critically panned by industry observers, who noticed that the action branding of the block - which had added shows such as ''[[Generation O!]]'', ''[[Scooby-Doo]]'', and ''[[The Nightmare Room]]'', a live-action series created by ''[[Goosebumps]]'' author [[R. L. Stine]] - did not translate content-wise. In spring 2002, Kids' WB announced that they would drop the Toonami name from their weekday lineup, once again making the Toonami brand exclusive to Cartoon Network.\n\nThe TIE, ''Lockdown'', aired between September 17\u201321, 2001, and included the introduction of [[CartoonNetwork.com#Online|CartoonNetwork.com's]] first [[Massively multiplayer online role-playing game|MMORPG]], as well as a record-breaking amount of page views and ratings for the network.<ref>{{cite web|title=Cartoon Network Breaks Rating Records in 2001|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2002-03-11/cartoon-network-breaks-rating-records-in-2001|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012|date=March 11, 2002}}</ref> In ''Lockdown'' T.O.M. fights to save the Absolution from an attack by a giant trash compactor.<ref>{{cite web|last=King|first=Brad|title=Game Is on for Cartoon Host|url=https://www.wired.com/techbiz/media/news/2001/09/46529|work=Wired.com|publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast|accessdate=April 1, 2012|date=September 17, 2001}}</ref> ''Trapped in Hyperspace'', the next TIE, ran the week of September 16\u201320, 2002. Sara gets taken offline by a computer virus named Swayzak (whose voice actor is unknown but is speculated to be [[Khary Payton]]), and TOM is trapped in hyperspace. He manages to defeat Swayzak before the Absolution hits Earth.<ref>{{cite web|last=Harris|first=Jeff|title=Toonami Becomes Trapped in Hyperspace|url=http://www.toonzone.net/forums/showthread.php?48019-Trapped-In-Hyperspace-Official-Press-Release|work=ToonZone.net|accessdate=April 1, 2012|date=September 12, 2002}}{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The game tie-in for this event is lost.\n\nDuring the week of February 24\u201328, 2003, Cartoon Network aired on Toonami \"Giant Robot Week,\" a five-day special based on [[mecha]] series, which were licensed by [[A.D. Vision]].  The series shown were ''[[Neon Genesis Evangelion]]'', ''[[Gigantor]]'', ''[[Robotech]]'', ''[[Martian Successor Nadesico]]'', and ''[[Dai-Guard]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Evangelion, Nadesico, Dai-Guard, Robotech to Air on Cartoon Network|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2003-01-28/evangelion-nadesico-dai-guard-robotech-to-air-on-cartoon-network|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|date=January 28, 2003|accessdate=September 12, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 2001, Cartoon Network released ''[[Toonami: Deep Space Bass]]'', the official soundtrack album to the TV block.\n\n====2003\u20132007: T.O.M. 3 era====\nIn March 2003, TOM was revamped into a more muscular figure. This was explained in-universe as him being rebuilt after fighting a space pirate. His voice also became more humanlike.\n\nIn September 2003, a mini series premiered introducing a new, [[2D computer graphics|2D]] universe. ''[[Immortal Grand Prix]]'' (''IGPX''), created by Toonami producers Sean Akins and Jason DeMarco, and produced by [[anime]] studio [[Production I.G]], aired in five short installments, serving as a pilot for the second Toonami original series, which premiered in November 2005<ref>{{cite web|last=Bynum|first=Aaron H.|title=CN Upfront: TOONAMI Programming|url=http://www.animationinsider.net/article.php?articleID=597|work=AnimationInsider.net|accessdate=April 2, 2012|date=February 16, 2005}}</ref>\n\nOn April 17, 2004, Toonami was moved from weekday afternoons to a Saturday evening slot, where it aired regularly for four hours starting at 7:00&nbsp;pm EST.<ref name=\"miguzi\">{{cite web|title=Cartoon Network Announces New Action-Adventure Programming Strategy|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/press-release/2004-02-26/cartoon-network-announces-new-action-adventure-programming-strategy|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 2, 2012|date=February 26, 2004}}</ref> A new lighter-toned action block, Miguzi, to weekdays in its place.<ref name=\"miguzi\"/> Toonami also replaced the block known as Saturday Video Entertainment System (SVES).  One reason for the move from weekdays to Saturday nights was because some of the shows on the weekday lineup became too violent for a weekday broadcast on the network. The new Toonami lineup showcased anime such as ''[[Naruto]]'', ''Rave Master'', ''[[Duel Masters]]'', ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam SEED]]'', ''[[One Piece (TV series)|One Piece]]'', ''[[Bobobo-bo Bo-bobo]]'', ''[[Zatch Bell]]'', and ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Chronicles]]'', as well as premiered North American productions including ''[[Teen Titans (TV series)|Teen Titans]]'', ''[[Megas XLR]]'', ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]'', and ''[[IGPX]]'', Toonami's first and only original production co-produced by [[Production I.G]] and [[Bandai Entertainment]]. Sara got a full body during this period, and became more anime-esque, along with her voice actress being changed to British actress and ''Red Dwarf'' star [[Samantha Robson]].\n\nAlthough ''[[Megas XLR]]'' was the first original American-made franchise to actually debut on the block, it was initially a Cartoon Network original that was planned to air on Friday nights.  Other Cartoon Network action properties, namely ''[[Samurai Jack]]'', ''[[Teen Titans (TV series)|Teen Titans]]'', and ''[[Justice League (TV series)|Justice League]]'', aired on Toonami, but were not exclusive to the block until their final seasons.\n\n====2007\u20132008: T.O.M. 4 era and cancellation====\nOn January 27, 2007, a [[teaser trailer|teaser]] commercial aired during the ''[[Xiaolin Showdown]]'' marathon on Cartoon Network, featuring closeup shots of larger Clydes (the remote robot explorers that have been a fixture of Toonami since the beginning) and two new robot A.I's along with the date \"3/17/07\" and T.O.M.'s chest emblem glowing blue. On March 17, Toonami celebrated its 10th anniversary with a new packaging and numerous [[Montage (filmmaking)|montages]] celebrating the block. T.O.M. was revamped into a shorter robot, who was a commander of a jungle control room and aided by two new robots, Flash ([[Dave Wittenberg]]) and D ([[Tom Kenny]]). The montages included a look at past hosts, former logos, and a decade's worth of clips and [[voice-over]]s from shows that aired on Toonami. There were a total of four montages, each with different clips, and three were one minute long.\n\nAs part of the anniversary (and to coincide with Cartoon Network's March Movie Madness event), Toonami planned another month of movies:\n* March 3 \u2013 ''[[The Invincible Iron Man (film)|The Invincible Iron Man]]''\n* March 10 \u2013 ''[[Mosaic (film)|Mosaic]]''\n* March 17 \u2013 ''[[Hellboy: Blood and Iron]]''\n* March 24 \u2013 ''[[Stan Lee Presents: The Condor]]''\n* March 31 \u2013 ''[[Spirited Away]]'' and ''[[Teen Titans: Trouble in Tokyo]]''\n\nOn September 20, 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-09-20/cartoon-network-to-reportedly-end-toonami-tonight|title=Cartoon Network to End Toonami on September 20 (Updated)|date=September 20, 2008|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> at the [[Anime Weekend Atlanta]] convention in Atlanta, Georgia, Cartoon Network announced that they had cancelled the Toonami block due to low ratings. Toonami then aired its final broadcast later that same evening. The final show to air on the block was a rerun of ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' at 10:30 PM. Employees who worked on the block moved to other parts of the channel, except for Dennis Moloney, who left Turner to work for [[Disney]]. Toonami Jetstream remained with the Toonami name until January 30, 2009. At the end of Toonami's final airing, T.O.M. 4 ended the block with a brief, final monologue, backed by the song \"Cascade\" by [[Tycho (musician)|Tycho]]:\n\n{{cquote|Well, [[The End (The Doors song)|this is the end, beautiful friends.]] After more than 11 years, this is Toonami's final broadcast. It's been a lot of fun, and we'd like to thank each and every one of you who made this journey with us. Toonami wouldn't have been anything without you. Hopefully, we've left you with some good memories. So, until we meet again, [[The Outsiders (novel)|stay gold.]] [[Cowboy Bebop|Bang.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/video/index.html?episodeID=8a250ab033ff6e9301343946df930141 |title=Videos &#124; Watch Free Online Videos |publisher=Cartoon Network |date= |accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref>}}\n\nAfter Toonami's final episode on TV, Toonami Jetstream's subsequent shut down in 2009 marked the end of this incarnation until the brand's revival in 2012.\n\n===Evening block on Adult Swim (2012\u2013present)===\n====2012\u20132013====\nOn April 1, 2012, Adult Swim aired the Toonami block for their annual [[April Fools' Day]] prank, in which would be the annual airing of ''[[The Room (2003 film)|The Room]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geekosystem.com/april-fools-2012/|title=April Fools\u2019 2012 Around the Web|last=Eddy|first=Max|date=April 1, 2012|work=Geekosystem.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> After airing that week's scheduled episode of ''[[Bleach (TV series)|Bleach]]'', the Toonami-related programming continued throughout the night, featuring shows such as ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'', ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam Wing]]'', ''[[Tenchi Muyo! Ryo-Ohki|Tenchi Muyo!]]'', ''[[Outlaw Star]]'', ''[[The Big O]]'', ''[[Yu Yu Hakusho]]'', ''[[Blue Submarine No. 6]]'', ''[[Trigun]]'', [[Astro Boy (1963 TV series)|''Astro Boy'' (1963)]], and ''[[Gigantor]]''. The following day, Adult Swim posted a message to their [[Twitter]] page, simply stating, \"Want it back? Let us know. [[Hashtag|#]]BringBackToonami\".<ref>{{cite tweet |author= <nowiki>[adult swim]</nowiki> |user= adultswim|number= 187004036824834049 |date= April 2, 2012 |title= Want it back? Let us know. #BringBackToonami |access-date= April 3, 2012 }}</ref> On April 4, Adult Swim followed up this tweet with one stating, \"#BringBackToonami We've heard you. Thank you for your passion and interest - stay tuned.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |author= <nowiki>[adult swim]</nowiki> |user= adultswim|number= 187653853339074560 |date= April 4, 2012 |title= #BringBackToonami We've heard you. Thank you for your passion and interest - stay tuned. |access-date= April 4, 2012 }}</ref> On April 8, Adult Swim aired two bumpers about the Toonami tweets and answered with \"[we're listening]\" and \"[we're looking into it]\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Adult Swim: We're listening|url=http://www.theouthousers.com/index.php/news/entertainment-news/18936-adult-swim-were-listening.html|work=TheOuthouse.com|accessdate=April 9, 2012|date=April 9, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, Adult Swim posted a message on Facebook announcing that Toonami would return on May 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adultswim.com/shows/toonami/index.html |title=Toonami returns May 26 on Adult Swim |publisher=Adultswim.com |date= |accessdate=May 22, 2012}}</ref> The network issued a press release later that day confirming the block's revival as a Saturday late-night action block.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20120516007065/en|title=Adult Swim Announces Largest Programming Schedule Ever for 2012-13|location=Atlanta, GA|publisher=Adult Swim|agency=Business Wire|via=Business Wire|date=May 16, 2012|accessdate=May 21, 2012}}</ref> Toonami made its return on May 26, with an initial lineup consisting of current Adult Swim Action programs, along with premieres of ''[[Deadman Wonderland]]'' and ''[[Casshern Sins]]''. On August 18, ''[[Samurai 7]]'' and ''[[Eureka Seven]]'' replaced ''Deadman Wonderland'' and ''[[Cowboy Bebop]]''. In essence, the revived block is very similar to the Midnight Run of the original, airing uncut programming as well as having more mature themes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-07-31/samurai-7-anime-debuts-on-toonami-on-august-19 |title=Samurai 7 Anime Debuts on Toonami on August 19 |publisher= AnimeNewsNetwork.com |date=July 31, 2012 |accessdate=July 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn October 6, Toonami expanded to a full six hours; ''[[Sym-Bionic Titan]]'' and ''[[ThunderCats (2011 TV series)|ThunderCats]]'' were added to the block.<ref name=cru_toon>{{cite news|last=Green|first=Scott|title=Toonami Expands to Six Hours|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2012/09/26-1/toonami-expands-to-six-hours|accessdate=September 26, 2012|newspaper=Crunchyroll News|date=September 26, 2012}}</ref> ''[[Tenchi Muyo! GXP]]'' was announced as the next premiere on November 3, as was the return of ''[[Inuyasha]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Adult Swim's Toonami Block to Show Tenchi Muyo! GXP|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-11-03/adult-swim-toonami-block-to-show-tenchi-muyo-gxp|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=November 5, 2012|date=November 3, 2012}}</ref> On November 22, Toonami announced they would air uncut episodes of ''[[Naruto]]'', and confirmed that ''[[Bleach (TV series)|Bleach]]'' would enter reruns for eight weeks, beginning on December 1.<ref>{{cite web|title=Naruto to Run Uncut on Adult Swim's Toonami Block|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2012-11-22/naruto-to-run-uncut-on-adult-swim-toonami-block|work=Anime News Network|accessdate=November 23, 2012|date=November 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn January 6, 2013, Toonami introduced a new blue color scheme, after using a similar scheme to introduce ''Inuyasha'' on November 3 of the previous year. New episodes of ''Bleach'' began on January 26.  On February 16, ''[[Soul Eater (manga)|Soul Eater]]'' began airing on Toonami, replacing ''Samurai 7''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toonami.tumblr.com/post/42169576098/tv-guide-youre-an-asshole|title=TV GUIDE, YOU\u2019RE AN ASSHOLE.|date=February 3, 2013}}</ref> During [[MomoCon]], new designs for both T.O.M and the Absolution were unveiled, along with the announcement that overall design of the block would be changed.<ref name=\"toonami.tumblr.com\">{{cite web|url=http://toonami.tumblr.com/post/46385114366/april-27th-why-should-you-care-about-april-27th|title=Toonami|work=tumblr.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====2013\u20132019====\nOn April 27, 2013 Toonami premiered its new look, featuring the return of supporting host Sara (now voiced by Adult Swim staff member [[Dana Swanson]].) To kick off 2014, Toonami premiered the anime ''[[Space Dandy]]'' on January 4, even before Japan. The anime ran for two seasons and 26 episodes before ending that September. The block introduced a new aesthetic on April 6. This new look also featured the return of the ''[[Ninja Tune]]'' record label to Toonami.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toonami.tumblr.com/post/81694903800/lots-of-little-goodies-coming-tomorrow|title=Toonami|work=tumblr.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> ''Intruder II'', the first Total Immersion Event since Toonami's 2012 revival, began on November 7 and concluded on December 20, 2015 with Sonny Strait reprising his role as Invader with Steve Blum, who also is the invader and TOM 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://toonami.tumblr.com/post/132775382573/its-been-a-long-time-coming-intruder-ii-begins|title=Toonami|publisher=}}</ref> On December 2, Adult Swim announced that a new season of ''[[Sword Art Online]]'' in July 27, 2013 and  ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' was being produced. It ended up premiering on Toonami in March 2017.<ref name=SamJack2016>{{cite web|title=Toonami|url=http://toonami.tumblr.com/post/134405148218/adult-swim-is-excited-to-announce-that-jack-is|website=tumblr.com|accessdate=December 2, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/03/11/519807686/-samurai-jack-cartoon-to-air-final-season-12-years-later|title='Samurai Jack' Cartoon To Air Final Season, 12 Years Later|publisher=[[National Public Radio]]|website=[[NPR.org]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/article/samurai-jack-return-cartoon-network-next-year-229189|title=Samurai Jack to return next year on Adult Swim|website=[[The A.V. Club]]}}</ref> The conclusion of ''Intruder III'' in 2016 led to another new look to Toonami.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-07-02/toonami-runs-mamoru-oshii-production-i.g-micro-series-in-2017/.103880|title=Toonami Runs Mamoru Oshii, Production I.G's Micro-Series in 2017|work=Anime News Network|date=July 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn December 31, 2016, Toonami aired its first subtitled anime broadcast with the music video of [[Porter Robinson]] and [[Madeon]]'s ''[[Shelter (Porter Robinson and Madeon song)|Shelter]]'', produced in collaboration with [[A-1 Pictures]] and [[Crunchyroll]]. However, the subtitled parts in both the start and end of the music video have been removed due to an unknown error. As of right now, it is unknown that the full version of the music video could air in the future.\n\nOn March 20, 2018, Production I.G. and Adult Swim announced that two new seasons of [[FLCL]], ''FLCL Progressive'', and ''FLCL Alternative'' would premiere on Toonami in 2018, with the date set for June 2 at 11:30PM.<ref name=\"2016 reveal\">{{cite web|title=Toonami to Co-Produce 2 New FLCL Seasons|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2016-03-24/toonami-to-co-produce-2-new-flcl-seasons/.100222|website=Anime News Network|accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Toho involvement\">{{cite web|title=ANIME EXPO 2017: FLCL 2 AND 3 FIRST DETAILS, RELEASE WINDOW ANNOUNCED|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2017/07/02/anime-expo-2017-flcl-2-and-3-first-details-release-window-announced|website=IGN|accessdate=March 20, 2018|date=July 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsweek.com/flcl-season-2-3-adult-swim-853752|title=New \u2018FLCL\u2019 Seasons Premiere on Adult Swim this June|publisher=newsweek|access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/updated-adult-swim-announces-two-new-seasons-of-cult-a-1798245721|title=Adult Swim announces two new seasons of cult anime hit FLCL|website=[[The A.V. Club]]}}</ref> On [[April Fools' Day]] 2018, Toonami was entirely dubbed in Japanese and kicked the prank off by airing a preview of the first episode of ''FLCL Alternative'' in Japanese with English subtitles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/4/2/17180894/flcl-3-alternative-toonami-adult-swim-april-fools|title=FLCL season 3 premieres as Adult Swim\u2019s April Fools\u2019 prank|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|website=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]}}</ref> The Toonami logo was also changed to Japanese (stylized as \u30c8\u30a6\u30ca\u30df). Toonami followed the sneak preview by airing the film ''[[Mind Game (film)|Mind Game]]'' and aired programming after that was originally scheduled after ''Black Clover'', except ''Iron-Blooded Orphans'', in original Japanese with English subtitles. TOM was voiced by Masa Kanome, a Japanese stunt actor who had been in a Wolverine movie, and Sara was voiced by Fusako Shiotani.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/adult-swim-celebrates-this-years-april-fools-by-running-1824238556|title=Adult Swim celebrates this year's April Fools by running a new FLCL episode months ahead of schedule|website=[[The A.V. Club]]}}</ref>\n\nOn September 29, Toonami expanded to seven full hours from 9 PM to 4 AM with ''[[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]'' as the marquee addition.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/2018/09/12/toonami-schedule-anime-expand-boruto-dragon-ball/|title=Toonami Expands Program With New Schedule, Shows|work=Comicbook|accessdate=September 12, 2018}}</ref> On December 13, it was announced that Toonami would remove ''Dragon Ball Z Kai'' and ''Samurai Jack'' from its lineup, cutting the block down to 6 hours. Also, the block would be moved back and would air from 11PM-5AM, starting on January 5, 2019, because of Adult Swim taking back the 8pm hour from Cartoon Network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Toonami/photos/a.1442483259375850/2053278171629686/?type=3|title=Toonami's new year schedule|website=Facebook|accessdate=December 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 24, it was announced that Toonami would remove ''Pop Team Epic'' and ''Iron-Blooded Orphans'' from its lineup, cutting the block down to 5 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Toonami/photos/a.1442483259375850/2077741649183338/?type=3&theater|title=Toonami\u2019s going back to our sweet spot!|website=facebook|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 13, 2019, Adult Swim announced that Toonami will be shifting its whole block thirty minutes earlier, starting at 10:30PM and ending at 3:30 AM, cutting a half hour rerun of ''[[Family Guy]]''. The changes will begin on May 25, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/anime/2019/05/13/toonami-schedule-change-may-25-attack-on-titan-season-3-part-2/|title=Toonami Announces Major May Schedule Shift|website=comicbook|accessdate=May 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn May 24, 2019, MomoCon announced that a new T.I.E., ''The Forge'', will begin airing on November 9.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ToonamiNews/status/1132079941007355904|title=Toonami's \"The Forge\" Coming November 9th|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=May 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn June 27, 2019, it was announced that Toonami will be shifting its whole block back at 11:00PM and ending at 4:00 AM, in addition to premiering ''[[Food Wars!: Shokugeki no Soma]]'' at 1:00AM. The changes will begin on July 6, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Toonami/photos/a.1442483259375850/2175293802761455/?type=3|title=Toonami Reveals Surprising July Schedule Shift|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> On July 4th at Anime Expo and on Facebook, it was announced that ''[[Demon Slayer: Kimetsu no Yaiba]]'' would be joining the block this Fall.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/1440408039583372/posts/2179755838981918?sfns=mo</ref> On July 7 at RTX 2019, it was announced that ''[[Gen:Lock]]'' would be joining the block on August 3.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/genlock-sets-adult-swim-premiere-date-1203260586/|title=Animated Series \u2018gen:LOCK\u2019 Sets Adult Swim Premiere Date|magazine=Variety|accessdate=July 7, 2019}}</ref> On August 16, it was announced that Toonami will expand 30 minutes and reshuffling its block with ''[[Dr. Stone]]'' at 12:00 AM.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/1440408039583372/posts/2208431249447710?sfns=mo|title=Dr. Stone coming to Toonami|publisher=Facebook|accessdate=August 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2020\u2013present====\nOn January 8, 2020, it was announced that ''[[Sword Art Online: Alicization|Sword Art Online: Alicization \u2013 War of Underworld]]'' would premiere on the network on January 18.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2020/01/08-1/sword-art-online-alicization-war-of-the-underworld-hits-toonami-on-january-18 |title=Sword Art Online Alicization War Of The Underworld Hits Toonami On January 18 |last=Luster |first=Joesph |date=January 8, 2020 |website=Crunchyroll}}</ref> On January 23, it was announced that Toonami would be reducing the block to five hours, as ''Fire Force'' was ending its run; the new block aired from 11:00 PM to 4:00 AM.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bubbleblabber.com/adult-swim-schedule-updates-new-toonami-schedule-for-february-ballmastrz-9009-season-two-gets-start-date-and-time/|title=Adult Swim Schedule Updates: New Toonami Schedule For February ; Ballmastrz: 9009 Season Two Gets Start Date And Time|publisher=bubbleblabber|accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref> On February 6, it was announced that the block would lose another one and a half hours, as ''Dr. Stone'' was ending its run, while reruns of ''The Promised Neverland'' and ''Attack on Titan'' would also cease. This reduced the length of the block to three and a half hours, which aired from 11:30 PM to 3:00 AM.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ToonamiNews/status/1225485729557549066|title=Toonami Delays New My Hero Academia Episode in Schedule Shift|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=February 6, 2020}}</ref> On April 8, it was announced that Toonami would be reduced to a three-hour block, as ''Sword Art Online: Alicization - War of Underworld'' was ending its run.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/anime/2020/04/08/toonami-new-schedule-anime-april-2020-shorter/|title=Toonami Announces New Schedule with Shortened Airtime|publisher=comicbook|accessdate=April 8, 2020}}</ref> On April 15, it was announced that ''[[Paranoia Agent]]''  would premiere on April 25 and that ''Food Wars: Shokugeki no Soma'' would be removed from the block until a new agreement was struck for the next three seasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-news/2020/04/15/cartoon-networks-toonami-adds-satoshi-kons-paranoia-agent-tv-anime-in-latest-schedule-update|title=Cartoon Network's Toonami Adds Satoshi Kon's Paranoia Agent TV Anime In Latest Schedule Update|publisher=Crunchyroll|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Online video services==\n===Toonami Reactor===\nOn March 26, 2001, Cartoon Network launched Toonami Reactor, their first online streaming video service.<ref>{{cite web|title=Large Toonami Updates|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2001-03-27/large-toonami-updates|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012|date=March 27, 2001}}</ref> The three-month service featured streaming episodes from ''Dragon Ball Z'' and ''[[Space Battleship Yamato|Star Blazers]]'', the latter of which was an online-exclusive series. Editorial content was provided by the now-defunct ''[[Animerica|Animerica Magazine]]'', published by [[VIZ Media]]. After the three-month \"trial run\" was over, Cartoon Network took it offline and completely revamped it.\n\nOn November 14, 2001, Cartoon Network relaunched Toonami Reactor with all online-exclusive programs such as ''[[Star Blazers]]'', ''[[Patlabor: The TV Series]]'', ''[[Captain Harlock|Harlock Saga]]'', and ''[[Record of Lodoss War]]'', as well as videos from Daft Punk and Toonami-themed games.  In the summer of 2002, Toonami Reactor was revamped again under the Adult Swim aegis and, in a joint venture with VIZ's ''[[Weekly Shonen Jump]]'', programmed it as \"Adult Swim Pipeline.\" It featured episodes and/or manga chapters from ''[[One Piece]]'', ''[[Naruto]]'', ''[[Shaman King]]'', ''[[Yu Yu Hakusho]]'', and ''[[Sand Land]].''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adultswim.com/pipeline/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030411064900/http://www.adultswim.com/pipeline/index.html|title=Adult Swim - Pipeline|archivedate=April 11, 2003|work=adultswim.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://adultswim.com/pipeline/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030207193313/http://adultswim.com/pipeline/index.html|title=Adult Swim|archivedate=February 7, 2003|work=adultswim.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Toonami Jetstream===\n{{main|Toonami Jetstream}}\nOn April 25, 2006, Cartoon Network and VIZ Media announced plans<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/pressrelease.php?id=1685|title=Cartoon Network and VIZ Media Announce Broadband Joint Venture, Toonami Jetstream|date=April 25, 2006|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> to launch [[Toonami Jetstream]], a new ad-supported streaming video service featuring Toonami series like ''Naruto'', ''Samurai Jack'', ''Megas XLR'', and ''IGPX'', and the Internet [[webcast]] premieres of ''[[Hikaru no Go]]'', ''[[M\u00c4R]]'', ''[[Eyeshield 21]]'', ''[[The Prince of Tennis]], [[MegaMan Star Force]]'', ''[[Kiba (anime)|Kiba]]'', ''[[MegaMan NT Warrior]]'', and ''[[Zoids: Genesis]]'', the latter two of which were never streamed.\n\nToonami Jetstream launched on July 17, 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogcritics.org/scitech/article/cartoon-networks-toonami-jetstream-to-begin/|title=Cartoon Network's Toonami Jetstream to Begin Streaming Video|author=TeevBlogger|date=April 28, 2006|work=Blogcritics.org|publisher=Technorati|accessdate=April 1, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017184326/http://blogcritics.org/scitech/article/cartoon-networks-toonami-jetstream-to-begin/|archivedate=October 17, 2011}}</ref> (after a brief unofficial sneak preview that began on July 14), and offered episodes of ''Naruto'', ''Hikaru no Go'', ''M\u00c4R'', ''[[Zatch Bell!]]'', ''Pok\u00e9mon'', ''[[Blue Dragon (video game)|Blue Dragon]]'', ''Samurai Jack'', ''Kiba'', ''[[Storm Hawks]]'' and ''[[Transformers: Animated]]''.\n\nOn January 31, 2009, Toonami Jetstream was discontinued.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2009-01-31/toonami-jetstream-video-streaming-service-shuts-down|title=Toonami Jetstream Video-Streaming Service Shuts Down|date=January 31, 2009|work=AnimeNewsNetwork.com|accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> Since then, many of the shows aired until cancellation aired on Cartoon Network Video on its main website.\n\nIn 2012, Adult Swim rebranded their action videos section as \"Toonami shows.\" It initially featured content from ''[[Durarara!!]]'', which never aired on the block.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adultswim.com/shows/index.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120816034804/http://www.adultswim.com/shows/index.html|title=Watch TV Show Episodes and Clips for Free from Adult Swim|archivedate=August 16, 2012|work=adultswim.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Toonami Pre-Flight===\nOn February 27, 2015, adultswim.com launched the online show ''Toonami: Pre-Flight'' hosted by Toonami producers Jason DeMarco and Gill Austin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adultswim.com/preflight|title=Adult Swim Streams - Live Stream|publisher=|accessdate=December 30, 2016}}</ref><!-- As of toonami.com/preflight --> The first two episodes premiered on a Friday at 5:00&nbsp;p.m. Eastern time, and was then moved to Tuesday at 5:00&nbsp;p.m. Eastern time until September 25, 2015, when the show was moved back to Fridays at 6:30&nbsp;p.m. Eastern time. Each episode features a series highlight, a weekly topic and other featurettes like sneak peeks at promos and spots, as well as announcements, and segments from voiceover talent [[Steve Blum]] and Dana Swanson. Toonami has also done panels from [[MomoCon]], [[San Diego Comic-Con International|San Diego Comic-Con]], [[Dragon Con]] and [[Anime Expo]] which they've streamed as part of Pre-Flight either live or on tape delay.\n\n=== Crunchyroll ===\nThe anime-oriented streaming service [[Crunchyroll]] became a sibling asset to Adult Swim after [[AT&T]]'s acquisition of [[Time Warner]], and its subsequent acquisition of the remaining shares in AT&T's existing venture [[Otter Media]]. In March 2019, after both Adult Swim and Otter were placed under Warner Bros. as part of a corporate reorganization, it was announced that there would be synergies between Toonami and the service. The two properties had already announced a collaboration on [[Blade Runner (franchise)#Blade Runner: Black Lotus (2019)|''Blade Runner: Black Lotus'']], an anime series set within the ''[[Blade Runner]]'' universe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/otter-media-acquired-att-crunchyroll-fullscreen-rooster-teeth-1202441941/|title=AT&T Acquires Rest Of Otter Media To Fold Into New WarnerMedia|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|author=Patrick Hipes|date=August 7, 2018|accessdate=October 26, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/3/12/18261643/adult-swim-crunchyroll-anime-series|title=Adult Swim and Crunchyroll are hooking up to bring more anime to TV|last=Frank|first=Allegra|date=2019-03-12|website=Polygon|access-date=2019-03-12}}</ref>\n\n==Programming==\n{{main|List of programs broadcast by Toonami}}\n\n===Cartoon Network (1997\u20132008) / Kids' WB (2001\u20132002)===\n;1997\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[ThunderCats (1985 TV series)|ThunderCats]]'' <small>(1985 series)</small>\n* ''Cartoon Roulette'' <small>(composed of ''[[Space Ghost (TV series)]]'', ''[[Birdman and the Galaxy Trio]]'', ''[[The Herculoids]]'', ''[[Mightor]]'', ''[[Shazzan]]'', ''[[Teen Force]]'', ''[[The Impossibles (TV series)|The Impossibles]]'', and the 1940s ''[[Superman (1940s cartoons)|Superman]]'' cartoons)</small>\n* ''[[Voltron (1984 TV series)|Voltron]]''\n* ''[[The Real Adventures of Jonny Quest]]''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n;1998\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Robotech (TV series)|Robotech]]''\n* ''[[Beast Wars: Transformers]]''\n* ''[[Sailor Moon (TV series)|Sailor Moon]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball Z]] ''\n* ''[[Super Friends]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;1999\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[ReBoot]]''\n* ''[[The Powerpuff Girls]]''\n* ''[[Ronin Warriors]]''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2000\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[G-Force: Guardians of Space]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam Wing]]''\n* ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]''\n* ''[[Tenchi Muyo! Ryo-Ohki]]''\n* ''[[Tenchi Universe]]''\n* ''[[Tenchi in Tokyo]]''\n* ''[[Blue Submarine No. 6]]''\n* ''[[Superman: The Animated Series]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2001\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Outlaw Star]]''\n* ''[[The Big O]]''\n* ''[[Cardcaptors]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam: The 08th MS Team]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball (anime)|Dragon Ball]]''\n* ''[[Batman Beyond]]''\n* ''[[Zoids: New Century]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam 0080: War in the Pocket]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2002\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Hamtaro]]''\n* ''[[Zoids: Chaotic Century]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Fighter G Gundam]]''\n* ''[[He-Man and the Masters of the Universe (2002 TV series)|He-Man and the Masters of the Universe]]''\n* ''[[Transformers: Armada]]''\n* ''[[G.I. Joe: A Real American Hero (1985 TV series)|G.I. Joe]]''\n* ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' <small>(original series)</small>\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2003\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[.hack//Sign]]''\n* ''[[Yu Yu Hakusho]]''\n* ''[[Rurouni Kenshin]]''\n* ''[[Justice League (TV series)|Justice League]]''\n* ''[[Cyborg 009|Cyborg 009: The Cyborg Soldier]]''\n* ''[[Superior Defender Gundam Force]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball GT]]''\n* ''[[Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|Star Wars: Clone Wars]]''\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2004\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Duel Masters]]''\n* ''[[Astro Boy (2003 TV series)|Astro Boy]]''\n* ''[[Transformers: Energon]]''\n* ''[[Jackie Chan Adventures]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam SEED]]''\n* ''[[Megas XLR]]''\n* ''[[Rave Master]]''\n* ''[[Teen Titans (TV series)|Teen Titans]]''\n* ''[[Justice League Unlimited]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2005\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[D.I.C.E.]]''\n* ''[[Zatch Bell!]]''\n* ''[[The Batman (TV series)|The Batman]]''\n* ''[[One Piece (TV series)|One Piece]]''\n* ''[[Transformers: Cybertron]]''\n* ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! Duel Monsters|Yu-Gi-Oh!]]''\n* ''[[Naruto]]''\n* ''[[Bobobo-bo Bo-bobo]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball Z]]'' <small>(uncut)</small>\n* ''[[Immortal Grand Prix|IGPX]]'' <small>(television series)</small>\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2006\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Wulin Warriors]]''\n* ''[[Pok\u00e9mon Chronicles]]''\n* ''[[Fantastic Four: World's Greatest Heroes]]''\n* ''[[Pok\u00e9mon: Battle Frontier]]''\n* ''[[Yu-Gi-Oh! GX]]''\n* ''[[M\u00c4R]]''\n* ''[[The Prince of Tennis]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2007\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Mega Man Star Force (anime)|Mega Man Star Force]]''\n* ''[[Storm Hawks]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2008\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Bakugan Battle Brawlers]]''\n* ''[[Blue Dragon (anime)|Blue Dragon]]''\n* ''[[Ben 10: Alien Force]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Adult Swim (2012\u2013present)===\n;2012\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Bleach (TV series)|Bleach]]''\n* ''[[Deadman Wonderland]]''\n* ''[[Casshern Sins]]''\n* ''[[Fullmetal Alchemist: Brotherhood]]''\n* ''[[Ghost in the Shell: S.A.C 2nd GIG]]''\n* ''[[Cowboy Bebop]]''\n* ''[[Ghost in the Shell: Stand Alone Complex]]''\n* ''[[Samurai 7]]''\n* ''[[Eureka Seven]]''\n* ''[[Sym-Bionic Titan]]''\n* ''[[ThunderCats (2011 TV series)|ThunderCats]]'' <small>(2011 series)</small>\n* ''[[Inuyasha]]''\n* ''[[Tenchi Muyo! GXP]]''\n* ''[[Naruto]]'' <small>(uncut)</small>\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2013\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Soul Eater (manga)|Soul Eater]]''\n* ''[[Immortal Grand Prix|IGPX]]'' <small>(television series)</small>\n* ''[[One Piece (TV series)|One Piece]]'' <small>(uncut)</small>\n* ''[[Sword Art Online]]''\n* ''[[The Big O|The Big O II]]''\n* ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]''\n* ''[[FLCL]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2014\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Space Dandy]]''\n* ''[[Naruto#Naruto: Shippuden|Naruto: Shippuden]]'' <small>(uncut)</small>\n* ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' <small>(original series / Seasons 1\u20134)</small>\n* ''[[Blue Exorcist]]''\n* ''[[Black Lagoon]]''\n* ''[[Attack on Titan]]''\n* ''[[Black Lagoon|Black Lagoon: The Second Barrage]]''\n* ''[[Beware the Batman]]''\n* ''[[Gurren Lagann]]''\n* ''[[Hellsing Ultimate]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball Z#Dragon Ball Z Kai|Dragon Ball Z Kai]]'' <small>(uncut)</small>\n* ''[[Inuyasha: The Final Act]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2015\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Kill la Kill]]''\n* ''[[Sword Art Online II]]''\n* ''[[Michiko & Hatchin]]''\n* ''[[Akame ga Kill!]]''\n* ''[[Parasyte|Parasyte -the maxim-]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2016\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Samurai Champloo]]''\n* ''[[Dimension W]]''\n* ''[[Hunter \u00d7 Hunter]]'' <small>(2011 series)</small>\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam: Iron-Blooded Orphans]]''\n* ''[[One-Punch Man]]''\n* ''[[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure (2012 TV series)|JoJo's Bizarre Adventure: The Animation]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2017\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Dragon Ball Super]]''\n* ''[[Dragon Ball Z#Dragon Ball Z Kai|Dragon Ball Z Kai: The Final Chapters]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam Unicorn|Mobile Suit Gundam Unicorn RE:0096]]''\n* ''[[Samurai Jack]]'' <small>(revival series / Season 5)</small>\n* ''[[Tokyo Ghoul]]''\n* ''[[Lupin the 3rd Part IV: The Italian Adventure]]''\n* ''[[Tokyo Ghoul \u221aA]]''\n* ''[[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure: Stardust Crusaders]]''\n* ''[[Outlaw Star]]'' <small>(HD)</small>\n* ''[[Black Clover]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2018\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[My Hero Academia]]''\n* ''[[FLCL|FLCL Progressive]]''\n* ''[[Pop Team Epic]]''\n* ''[[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure: Diamond Is Unbreakable]]''\n* ''[[FLCL|FLCL Alternative]]''\n* ''[[Boruto: Naruto Next Generations]]''\n* ''[[Mob Psycho 100]]''\n* ''[[Megalo Box]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2019\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Sword Art Online: Alicization]]''\n* ''[[The Promised Neverland]]''\n* ''[[Lupin the Third Part 5]]''\n* ''[[Food Wars!: Shokugeki no Soma]]''\n* ''[[Mobile Suit Gundam: The Origin|Mobile Suit Gundam: The Origin - Advent of the Red Comet]]''\n* ''[[Fire Force]]''\n* ''[[Gen:Lock]]''\n* ''[[Dr. Stone]]''\n* ''[[Demon Slayer: Kimetsu no Yaiba]]''\n* ''[[JoJo's Bizarre Adventure: Golden Wind]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n;2020\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* ''[[Sword Art Online: Alicization|Sword Art Online: Alicization \u2013 War of Underworld]]''\n* ''[[Paranoia Agent]]''\n* ''[[Uzumaki]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==International==\nOutside the United States, Cartoon Network aired Toonami blocks in Australia from 2001 to 2006. In the United Kingdom, Toonami was a standalone channel from 2003 to 2007. In December 2012, Toonami was launched as a standalone channel in Asia-Pacific. Similar channels were launched in India in 2015, France in 2016 and Africa in 2017. The Southeast Asian and Indian channels have since been closed.\n\n===Australia===\n{{Main|Toonami (Australian TV programming block)}}\nThe programming block was launched in 2001 in Australia as a weekend block on [[Cartoon Network (Australia and New Zealand)|Cartoon Network]]. It aired on Saturday from 6:00 pm to 8:00 pm and on Sunday from 3:00 pm to 5:00 pm with a repeat on both nights from 11:00 pm to 1:00 am. The programming was then converted to a weekday block shortly there after. The programming was dropped from the channel in August 2006.\n\n===France===\n{{Main|Toonami (France)}}\nFrench version of the Toonami television channel was launched on February 11, 2016. It is operated by [[Turner Broadcasting System Europe]].\n\n===India===\n{{Main|Toonami (India)}}\nAn Indian version of Toonami was first launched as a block in 2001 and was then followed by a stand-alone channel in 2015. It ceased operations in May 15, 2018.\n\n===Latin America===\n{{Main|Toonami (Latin America)}}\nOn December 2, 2002, Cartoon Network premiered Toonami block, replacing a similarly-themed block, Talisman. The weekend block of Toonami was then replaced by the premiere of Adult Swim in Latin America on October 7, 2005. In 2007, Cartoon Network cut the Toonami block completely from the channel.\n\n===Pakistan===\nToonami was launched as a programming block in Pakistan on [[Cartoon Network (Pakistan)|Cartoon Network]] and ran from 2004\u20132013.\n\n===Southeast Asia===\n{{Main|Toonami (Southeast Asia)}}\nA stand-alone Toonami channel was launched in Southeast Asia replacing [[Boomerang (Southeast Asian TV channel)|Boomerang]] on December 1, 2012. Although it replaced Boomerang, the channel was relaunched in 2015 alongside Toonami. The channel shut down on March 31, 2018 making it the longest running stand alone channel out all of them lasting 6 years.\n\n===Sub-Saharan Africa===\nA Toonami television channel was launched in sub-Saharan Africa on June 1, 2017. It is available on Kwes\u00e9 satellite television platform.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/tv/turners-toonami-finds-africa-pay-tv-home/?doing_wp_cron=1496335314.8652520179748535156250 |title=Turner\u2019s Toonami Finds Africa Pay TV Home |date=2017-05-31 |website=Animation Magazine |language=en-US |access-date=2018-06-10}}</ref>\n\n===UK & Ireland===\n{{Main|Toonami (UK & Ireland)}}\nToonami was launched as a programming block on [[Cartoon Network (UK & Ireland)|Cartoon Network]] in the UK and Ireland in 2001. In October 2002, it then became part of [[CNX (TV channel)|CNX]], a new spin-off channel. Almost a year later, CNX was relaunched as Toonami in 2003 turning the block into a stand-alone channel. The channel shut down on May 24, 2007.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Television|United States|Anime and manga|Cartoon|Cartoon Network|1990s}}\n<!-- ({{NoMoreLinks}}) -->\n<!-- DO NOT ADD MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A COLLECTION OF LINKS ----- If you think that your link might be useful, instead of placing it here, put it on this article's discussion page first. Links that have not been verified WILL BE DELETED -->\n* {{Official website|https://www.adultswim.com/toonami/}}\n<!--\nDo not add Facebook and Twitter et al. There are MANY and all are linked from the campaign site.\n-->\n\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Toonami-anime}}\n{{Warner Bros.}}\n{{Cartoon Network}}\n{{Adult Swim original programming}}\n{{Williams Street}}\n{{Kids' WB}}\n{{KidsTVBlocksUS}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Toonami]]\n[[Category:Adult Swim]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network]]\n[[Category:Cartoon Network programming blocks]]\n[[Category:Williams Street]]\n[[Category:Television programming blocks in the United States]]\n[[Category:Anime television]]\n[[Category:1997 introductions]]\n[[Category:1997 establishments in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "MarcoPolo250", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBroadcast History", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toonami"}
